# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alcohol-fuel
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] The International Agency for Research on Cancer (IARC) has listed acetaldehyde as a Group 1 carcinogen.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is "one of the most frequently found air toxins with cancer risk greater than one in a million".
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] In 1835, Liebig named it "aldehyde", and in the middle of the century the name was altered to "acetaldehyde".
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] In 2013, global production was about 438,000 tonnes.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] Before 1962, ethanol and acetylene were the major sources of acetaldehyde.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] Since then, ethylene is the dominant feedstock.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] In the 1970s, the world capacity of the Wacker-Hoechst direct oxidation process exceeded two million tonnes annually.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] Smaller quantities can be prepared by the partial oxidation of ethanol in an exothermic reaction.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] This process typically is conducted over a silver catalyst at about 500–650 °C (950–1,200 °F).
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] This method is one of the oldest routes for the industrial preparation of acetaldehyde.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] Prior to the Wacker process and the availability of cheap ethylene, acetaldehyde was produced by the hydration of acetylene.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] The mechanism involves the intermediacy of vinyl alcohol, which tautomerizes to acetaldehyde.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] The reaction is conducted at 90–95 °C (194–203 °F), and the acetaldehyde formed is separated from water and mercury and cooled to 25–30 °C (77–86 °F).
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] In the wet oxidation process, iron(III) sulfate is used to reoxidize the mercury back to the mercury(II) salt.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] The resulting iron(II) sulfate is oxidized in a separate reactor with nitric acid.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] The enzyme Acetylene hydratase discovered in the strictly anaerobic bacterium *Pelobacter acetylenicus* can catalyze an analogous reaction without involving any compounds of mercury.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] However, it has thus far not been brought to any large-scale or commercial use.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] In this endothermic process, ethanol vapor is passed at 260–290 °C over a copper-based catalyst.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] The process was once attractive because of the value of the hydrogen coproduct, but in modern times is not economically viable.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] The hydroformylation of methanol with catalysts like cobalt, nickel, or iron salts also produces acetaldehyde, although this process is of no industrial importance.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] Similarly noncompetitive, acetaldehyde arises from synthesis gas with modest selectivity.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] The equilibrium constant is 6×10−7 at room temperature, thus that the relative amount of the enol form in a sample of acetaldehyde is very small.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] At room temperature, acetaldehyde (CH3CH=O) is more stable than vinyl alcohol (CH2=CHOH) by 42.7 kJ/mol: Overall the keto-enol tautomerization occurs slowly but is catalyzed by acids.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] Photo-induced keto-enol tautomerization is viable under atmospheric or stratospheric conditions.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] This photo-tautomerization is relevant to the Earth's atmosphere, because vinyl alcohol is thought to be a precursor to carboxylic acids in the atmosphere.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is a common electrophile in organic synthesis.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] In addition reactions acetaldehyde is prochiral.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] It is used primarily as a source of the "CH3C+H(OH)" synthon in aldol reactions and related condensation reactions.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] Grignard reagents and organolithium compounds react with MeCHO to give hydroxyethyl derivatives.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] In one of the more spectacular addition reactions, formaldehyde in the presence of calcium hydroxide adds to MeCHO to give pentaerythritol, C(CH2OH)4 and formate.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] In a Strecker reaction, acetaldehyde condenses with cyanide and ammonia to give, after hydrolysis, the amino acid alanine.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde can condense with amines to yield imines; for example, with cyclohexylamine to give *N*-ethylidenecyclohexylamine.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] These imines can be used to direct subsequent reactions like an aldol condensation.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] It is also a building block in the synthesis of heterocyclic compounds.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] In one example, it converts, upon treatment with ammonia, to 5-ethyl-2-methylpyridine ("aldehyde-collidine").
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] Three molecules of acetaldehyde condense to form "paraldehyde", a cyclic trimer containing C-O single bonds.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] Similarly condensation of four molecules of acetaldehyde give the cyclic molecule metaldehyde.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] Paraldehyde can be produced in good yields, using a sulfuric acid catalyst.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] Metaldehyde is only obtained in a few percent yield and with cooling, often using HBr rather than H2SO4 as the catalyst.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] At −40 °C (−40 °F) in the presence of acid catalysts, polyacetaldehyde is produced.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] There are two stereomers of paraldehyde and four of metaldehyde.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] The German chemist Valentin Hermann Weidenbusch (1821–1893) synthesized paraldehyde in 1848 by treating acetaldehyde with acid (either sulfuric or nitric acid) and cooling to 0 °C (32 °F).
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] He found it quite remarkable that when paraldehyde was *heated* with a trace of the same acid, the reaction went the other way, recreating acetaldehyde.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] Although vinyl alcohol is a tautomeric form of acetaldehyde (§ Tautomerization to vinyl alcohol), polyvinyl alcohol cannot be produced from acetaldehyde.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde forms a stable acetal upon reaction with ethanol under conditions that favor dehydration.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] The product, CH3CH(OCH2CH3)2, is formally named 1,1-diethoxyethane but is commonly referred to as "acetal".
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] This can cause confusion as "acetal" is more commonly used to describe compounds with the functional groups RCH(OR')2 or RR'C(OR'')2 rather than referring to this specific compound — in fact, 1,1-diethoxyethane is also described as the diethyl acetal of acetaldehyde.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is a precursor to vinylphosphonic acid, which is used to make adhesives and ion conductive membranes.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] In the liver, the enzyme alcohol dehydrogenase oxidizes ethanol into acetaldehyde, which is then further oxidized into harmless acetic acid by acetaldehyde dehydrogenase.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] These two oxidation reactions are coupled with the reduction of NAD+ to NADH.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] In the brain, the enzyme catalase is primarily responsible for oxidizing ethanol to acetaldehyde, and alcohol dehydrogenase plays a minor role.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] The last steps of alcoholic fermentation in bacteria, plants, and yeast involve the conversion of pyruvate into acetaldehyde and carbon dioxide by the enzyme pyruvate decarboxylase, followed by the conversion of acetaldehyde into ethanol.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] The latter reaction is again catalyzed by an alcohol dehydrogenase, now operating in the opposite direction.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] Many East Asian people have an ALDH2 mutation which makes them significantly less efficient at oxidizing acetaldehyde.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] On consuming alcohol, their bodies tend to accumulate excessive amounts of acetaldehyde, causing the so-called alcohol flush reaction.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] They develop a characteristic flush on the face and body, along with "nausea, headache and general physical discomfort".
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] Ingestion of the drug disulfiram, which inhibits ALDH2, leads to a similar reaction .
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] Traditionally, acetaldehyde was mainly used as a precursor to acetic acid.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] This application has declined because acetic acid is produced more efficiently from methanol by the Monsanto and Cativa processes.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is an important precursor to pyridine derivatives, pentaerythritol, and crotonaldehyde.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] Urea and acetaldehyde combine to give a useful resin.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] Acetic anhydride reacts with acetaldehyde to give ethylidene diacetate, a precursor to vinyl acetate, which is used to produce polyvinyl acetate.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] The global market for acetaldehyde is declining.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] Demand has been impacted by changes in the production of plasticizer alcohols, which has shifted because *n*-butyraldehyde is less often produced from acetaldehyde, instead being generated by hydroformylation of propylene.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] Likewise, acetic acid, once produced from acetaldehyde, is made predominantly by the lower-cost methanol carbonylation process.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] The impact on demand has led to increase in prices and thus slowdown in the market.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] China is the largest consumer of acetaldehyde in the world, accounting for almost half of global consumption in 2012.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] Major use has been the production of acetic acid.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] Other uses such as pyridines and pentaerythritol are expected to grow faster than acetic acid, but the volumes are not large enough to offset the decline in acetic acid.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] As a consequence, overall acetaldehyde consumption in China may grow slightly at 1.6% per year through 2018.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] Western Europe is the second-largest consumer of acetaldehyde worldwide, accounting for 20% of world consumption in 2012.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] As with China, the Western European acetaldehyde market is expected to increase only very slightly at 1% per year during 2012–2018.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] However, Japan could emerge as a potential consumer for acetaldehyde in the next five years due to newfound use in commercial production of butadiene.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] The supply of butadiene has been volatile in Japan and the rest of Asia.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] This should provide the much needed boost to the flat market, as of 2013.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] The threshold limit value is 25 ppm (STEL/ceiling value) and the MAK (Maximum Workplace Concentration) is 50 ppm.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] At 50 ppm acetaldehyde, no irritation or local tissue damage in the nasal mucosa is observed.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] When taken up by the organism, acetaldehyde is metabolized rapidly in the liver to acetic acid.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] Only a small proportion is exhaled unchanged.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] After intravenous injection, the half-life in the blood is approximately 90 seconds.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] Many serious cases of acute intoxication have been recorded.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde naturally breaks down in the human body.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is an irritant of the skin, eyes, mucous membranes, throat, and respiratory tract.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] This occurs at concentrations as low as 1000 ppm.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] Symptoms of exposure to this compound include nausea, vomiting, and headache.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] These symptoms may not happen immediately.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] The perception threshold for acetaldehyde in air is in the range between 0.07 and 0.25 ppm.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] At such concentrations, the fruity odor of acetaldehyde is apparent.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] Conjunctival irritations have been observed after a 15-minute exposure to concentrations of 25 and 50 ppm, but transient conjunctivitis and irritation of the respiratory tract have been reported after exposure to 200 ppm acetaldehyde for 15 minutes.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] In addition, acetaldehyde is damaging to DNA and causes abnormal muscle development as it binds to proteins.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde induces DNA interstrand crosslinks, a form of DNA damage.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] These can be repaired by either of two replication-coupled DNA repair pathways.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] The first is referred to as the FA pathway, because it employs gene products defective in Fanconi's anemia patients.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] This repair pathway results in increased mutation frequency and altered mutational spectrum.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] The second repair pathway requires replication fork convergence, breakage of the acetaldehyde crosslink, translesion synthesis by a Y-family DNA polymerase and homologous recombination.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] People with a genetic deficiency for the enzyme responsible for the conversion of acetaldehyde into acetic acid may have a greater risk of Alzheimer's disease.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] A study of 818 heavy drinkers found that those exposed to more acetaldehyde than normal through a genetic variant of the gene encoding for ADH1C, ADH1C*1, are at greater risk of developing cancers of the upper gastrointestinal tract and liver.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] The drug disulfiram (Antabuse) inhibits acetaldehyde dehydrogenase, an enzyme that oxidizes the compound into acetic acid.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] Metabolism of ethanol forms acetaldehyde before acetaldehyde dehydrogenase forms acetic acid, but with the enzyme inhibited, acetaldehyde accumulates.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] If one consumes ethanol while taking disulfiram, the hangover effect of ethanol is felt more rapidly and intensely (disulfiram-alcohol reaction).
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] As such, disulfiram is sometimes used as a deterrent for alcoholics wishing to stay sober.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is a potential contaminant in workplace, indoors, and ambient environments.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] Moreover, the majority of humans spend more than 90% of their time in indoor environments, increasing any exposure and the risk to human health.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] In a study in France, the mean indoor concentration of acetaldehydes measured in 16 homes was approximately seven times higher than the outside acetaldehyde concentration.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] The living room had a mean of 18.1±17.5 μg m−3 and the bedroom was 18.2±16.9 μg m−3, whereas the outdoor air had a mean concentration of 2.3±2.6 μg m−3.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] It has been concluded that volatile organic compounds (VOC) such as benzene, formaldehyde, acetaldehyde, toluene, and xylenes have to be considered priority pollutants with respect to their health effects.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] It has been pointed that in renovated or completely new buildings, the VOCs concentration levels are often several orders of magnitude higher.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] The main sources of acetaldehydes in homes include building materials, laminate, PVC flooring, varnished wood flooring, and varnished cork/pine flooring (found in the varnish, not the wood).
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] It is also found in plastics, oil-based and water-based paints, in composite wood ceilings, particle-board, plywood, treated pine wood, and laminated chipboard furniture.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] The use of acetaldehyde is widespread in different industries, and it may be released into waste water or the air during production, use, transportation and storage.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] Sources of acetaldehyde include fuel combustion emissions from stationary internal combustion engines and power plants that burn fossil fuels, wood, or trash, oil and gas extraction, refineries, cement kilns, lumber and wood mills and paper mills.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is also present in automobile and diesel exhaust.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] As a result, acetaldehyde is "one of the most frequently found air toxics with cancer risk greater than one in a million".
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] Natural tobacco polysaccharides, including cellulose, have been shown to be the primary precursors making acetaldehyde a significant constituent of tobacco smoke.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] It has been demonstrated to have a synergistic effect with nicotine in rodent studies of addiction.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is also the most abundant carcinogen in tobacco smoke; it is dissolved into the saliva while smoking.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde has been found in cannabis smoke.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] This finding emerged through the use of new chemical techniques that demonstrated the acetaldehyde present was causing DNA damage in laboratory settings.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] Many microbes produce acetaldehyde from ethanol, but they have a lower capacity to eliminate the acetaldehyde, which can lead to the accumulation of acetaldehyde in saliva, stomach acid, and intestinal contents.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] Fermented food and many alcoholic beverages can also contain significant amounts of acetaldehyde.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde, derived from mucosal or microbial oxidation of ethanol, tobacco smoke, and diet, appears to act as a cumulative carcinogen in the upper digestive tract of humans.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] According to European Commission's Scientific Committee on Consumer Safety's (SCCS) "Opinion on Acetaldehyde" (2012) the cosmetic products special risk limit is 5 mg/L and acetaldehyde should not be used in mouth-washing products.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde can be produced by the photo-oxidation of polyethylene terephthalate (PET), via a Type II Norrish reaction.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] Although the levels produced by this process are minute acetaldehyde has an exceedingly low taste/odor threshold of around 20–40 ppb and can cause an off-taste in bottled water.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] The level at which an average consumer could detect acetaldehyde is still considerably lower than any toxicity.
[src:alcohol-fuel/acetaldehyde] The yeast *Candida albicans* in patients with potentially carcinogenic oral diseases has been shown to produce acetaldehyde in quantities sufficient to cause problems.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] In chemistry, an **alcohol** (from Arabic *al-kuḥl* 'the kohl') is a type of organic compound that carries at least one hydroxyl (−OH) functional group bound to a saturated carbon atom.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] Alcohols range from the simple, like methanol and ethanol, to complex, like sugar alcohols and cholesterol.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] The presence of an OH group strongly modifies the properties of hydrocarbons, conferring hydrophilic (water-attracted) properties.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] The OH group provides a site at which many reactions can occur.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] The flammable nature of the exhalations of wine was already known to ancient natural philosophers such as Aristotle (384–322 BCE), Theophrastus (c.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] However, this did not immediately lead to the isolation of alcohol, even despite the development of more advanced distillation techniques in second- and third-century Roman Egypt.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] An important recognition, first found in one of the writings attributed to Jābir ibn Ḥayyān (ninth century CE), was that by adding salt to boiling wine, which increases the wine's relative volatility, the flammability of the resulting vapors may be enhanced.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] The distillation of wine is attested in Arabic works attributed to al-Kindī (c.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] 872–950), and in the 28th book of al-Zahrāwī's (Latin: Abulcasis, 936–1013) *Kitāb al-Taṣrīf* (later translated into Latin as *Liber servatoris*).
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] In the twelfth century, recipes for the production of *aqua ardens* ("burning water", i.e., alcohol) by distilling wine with salt started to appear in a number of Latin works, and by the end of the thirteenth century, it had become a widely known substance among Western European chemists.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] The works of Taddeo Alderotti (1223–1296) describe a method for concentrating alcohol involving repeated fractional distillation through a water-cooled still, by which an alcohol purity of 90% could be obtained.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] The medicinal properties of ethanol were studied by Arnald of Villanova (1240–1311 CE) and John of Rupescissa (c.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] 1310–1366), the latter of whom regarded it as a life-preserving substance able to prevent all diseases (the *aqua vitae* or "water of life", also called by John the *quintessence* of wine).
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] The word "alcohol" derives from the Arabic *kohl* (Arabic: الكحل, romanized: *al-kuḥl*), a powder used as an eyeliner.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] The first part of the word (*al-*) is the Arabic definite article, equivalent to *the* in English.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] The second part of the word (*kuḥl*) has several antecedents in Semitic languages, ultimately deriving from the Akkadian 𒎎𒋆𒁉𒍣𒁕 (*guḫlum*), meaning stibnite or antimony.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] Like its antecedents in Arabic and older languages, the term *alcohol* was originally used for the very fine powder produced by the sublimation of the natural mineral stibnite to form antimony trisulfide Sb2S3.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] It was considered to be the essence or "spirit" of this mineral.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] It was used as an antiseptic, eyeliner, and cosmetic.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] Later the meaning of alcohol was extended to distilled substances in general, and then narrowed again to ethanol, when "spirits" was a synonym for hard liquor.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] Paracelsus and Libavius both used the term *alcohol* to denote a fine powder, the latter speaking of an *alcohol* derived from antimony.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] At the same time Paracelsus uses the word for a volatile liquid; *alcool* or *alcool vini* occurs often in his writings.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] The 1657 *Lexicon Chymicum* by William Johnson glosses the word as "antimonium sive stibium." By extension, the word came to refer to any fluid obtained by distillation, including "alcohol of wine," the distilled essence of wine.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] Libavius in *Alchymia* (1594) refers to "vini alcohol vel vinum alcalisatum".
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] The term *ethanol* was invented in 1892, blending "ethane" with the "-ol" ending of "alcohol", which was generalized as a libfix.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] The term *alcohol* originally referred to the primary alcohol ethanol (ethyl alcohol), which is used as a drug and is the main alcohol present in alcoholic drinks.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] The suffix *-ol* appears in the International Union of Pure and Applied Chemistry (IUPAC) chemical name of all substances where the hydroxyl group is the functional group with the highest priority.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] When a higher priority group is present in the compound, the prefix *hydroxy-* is used in its IUPAC name.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] The suffix *-ol* in non-IUPAC names (such as paracetamol or cholesterol) also typically indicates that the substance is an alcohol.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] However, some compounds that contain hydroxyl functional groups have *trivial names* that do not include the suffix *-ol* or the prefix *hydroxy-*, e.g. the sugars glucose and sucrose.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] IUPAC nomenclature is used in scientific publications, and in writings where precise identification of the substance is important.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] In naming simple alcohols, the name of the alkane chain loses the terminal *e* and adds the suffix *-ol*, *e.g.*, as in "ethanol" from the alkane chain name "ethane".
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] When necessary, the position of the hydroxyl group is indicated by a number between the alkane name and the *-ol*: propan-1-ol for CH3CH2CH2OH, propan-2-ol for CH3CH(OH)CH3.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] If a higher priority group is present (such as an aldehyde, ketone, or carboxylic acid), then the prefix *hydroxy-*is used, e.g., as in 1-hydroxy-2-propanone (CH3C(O)CH2OH).
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] Compounds having more than one hydroxy group are called polyols.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] They are named using suffixes -diol, -triol, etc., following a list of the position numbers of the hydroxyl groups, as in propane-1,2-diol for CH3CH(OH)CH2OH (propylene glycol).
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] In cases where the hydroxy group is bonded to an sp2 carbon on an aromatic ring, the molecule is classified separately as a phenol and is named using the IUPAC rules for naming phenols.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] Phenols have distinct properties and are not classified as alcohols.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] In other less formal contexts, an alcohol is often called with the name of the corresponding alkyl group followed by the word "alcohol", e.g., methyl alcohol, ethyl alcohol.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] Propyl alcohol may be *n*-propyl alcohol or isopropyl alcohol, depending on whether the hydroxyl group is bonded to the end or middle carbon on the straight propane chain.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] As described under systematic naming, if another group on the molecule takes priority, the alcohol moiety is often indicated using the "hydroxy-" prefix.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] In archaic nomenclature, alcohols can be named as derivatives of methanol using "-carbinol" as the ending.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] For instance, (CH3)3COH can be named trimethylcarbinol.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] Alcohols are then classified into primary, secondary (*sec-*, *s-*), and tertiary (*tert-*, *t-*), based upon the number of carbon atoms connected to the carbon atom that bears the hydroxyl functional group.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] The respective numeric shorthands 1°, 2°, and 3° are sometimes used in informal settings.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] The primary alcohols have general formulas RCH2OH.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] The simplest primary alcohol is methanol (CH3OH), for which R = H, and the next is ethanol, for which R = CH3, the methyl group.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] Secondary alcohols are those of the form RR'CHOH, the simplest of which is 2-propanol (R = R' = CH3).
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] For the tertiary alcohols, the general form is RR'R"COH.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] The simplest example is *tert*-butanol (2-methylpropan-2-ol), for which each of R, R', and R" is CH3.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] In these shorthands, R, R', and R" represent substituents, alkyl or other attached, generally organic groups.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] Alcohols have a long history of myriad uses.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] Methanol is the most common industrial alcohol, with about 12 million tons/y produced in 1980.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] The combined capacity of the other alcohols is about the same, distributed roughly equally.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] With respect to acute toxicity, simple alcohols have low acute toxicities.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] Doses of several milliliters are tolerated.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] For pentanols, hexanols, octanols, and longer alcohols, LD50 range from 2–5 g/kg (rats, oral).
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] Methanol and ethylene glycol are more toxic than other simple alcohols.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] Their metabolism is affected by the presence of ethanol, which has a higher affinity for liver alcohol dehydrogenase.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] In this way, methanol will be excreted intact in urine.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] In general, the hydroxyl group makes alcohols polar.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] Those groups can form hydrogen bonds to one another and to most other compounds.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] Owing to the presence of the polar OH alcohols are more water-soluble than simple hydrocarbons.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] Methanol, ethanol, and propanol are miscible in water.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] 1-Butanol, with a four-carbon chain, is moderately soluble.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] Because of hydrogen bonding, alcohols tend to have higher boiling points than comparable hydrocarbons and ethers.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] The boiling point of the alcohol ethanol is 78.29 °C, compared to 69 °C for the hydrocarbon hexane, and 34.6 °C for diethyl ether.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] Alcohols occur widely in nature, as derivatives of glucose such as cellulose and hemicellulose, and in phenols and their derivatives such as lignin.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] Starting from biomass, 180 billion tons/y of complex carbohydrates (sugar polymers) are produced commercially (as of 2014).
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] Many other alcohols are pervasive in organisms, as manifested in other sugars such as fructose and sucrose, in polyols such as glycerol, and in some amino acids such as serine.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] Simple alcohols like methanol, ethanol, and propanol occur in modest quantities in nature, and are industrially synthesized in large quantities for use as chemical precursors, fuels, and solvents.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] Many alcohols are produced by hydroxylation, i.e., the installation of a hydroxy group using oxygen or a related oxidant.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] Hydroxylation is the means by which the body processes many poisons, converting lipophilic compounds into hydrophilic derivatives that are more readily excreted.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] Enzymes called hydroxylases and oxidases facilitate these conversions.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] Many industrial alcohols, such as cyclohexanol for the production of nylon, are produced by hydroxylation.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] In the Ziegler process, linear alcohols are produced from ethylene and triethylaluminium followed by oxidation and hydrolysis.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] The process generates a range of alcohols that are separated by distillation.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] Many higher alcohols are produced by hydroformylation of alkenes followed by hydrogenation.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] Such processes give fatty alcohols, which are useful for detergents.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] Industry produces low-weight molecular alcohols (e.g. ethanol, isopropanol, 2-butanol, and *tert*-butanol) through the acid-catalyzed hydration of alkenes, the latter typically from cracking fractions of distilled crude oil.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] Two implementations are employed: the direct and indirect methods.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] In the indirect method, the alkene is converted to a sulfate ester, which is subsequently hydrolyzed.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] The direct method eschews intermediates, instead using water to quench an intermediate carbocation.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] Less aggressive reagents suffice for vicinal difunctionalization.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] In industry, the diol ethylene glycol forms when ethylene oxide is hydrolyzed.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] In the laboratory, sulfuric acid also catalyzes hydration of alkenes to secondary or tertiary alcohols.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] More controllable net hydrations proceed in multiple steps, with a vicinally-functionalized intermediate.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] Thus oxymercuration initially forms an organomercury alcohol, which can then undergo reductive demetalation; and alkenes react with *N*-bromosuccinimide and water to form halohydrins.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] In hydroboration-oxidation and the related Mukaiyama hydration, an alkene is hydrometalated, then oxidized.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] Ethanol is obtained by fermentation of glucose (which is often obtained from starch) in the presence of yeast.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] Like ethanol, butanol can be produced by fermentation processes.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] *Saccharomyces* yeast are known to produce these higher alcohols at temperatures above 75 °F (24 °C).
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] The bacterium *Clostridium acetobutylicum* can feed on cellulose (also an alcohol) to produce butanol on an industrial scale.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] Primary alkyl halides react with aqueous NaOH or KOH to give alcohols in nucleophilic aliphatic substitution.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] Secondary and especially tertiary alkyl halides will give the elimination (alkene) product instead.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] Grignard reagents react with carbonyl groups to give secondary and tertiary alcohols.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] Related reactions are the Barbier reaction and the Nozaki–Hiyama–Kishi reaction.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] Aldehydes or ketones are reduced with sodium borohydride or lithium aluminium hydride (after an acidic workup).
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] Another reduction using aluminium isopropoxide is the Meerwein–Ponndorf–Verley reduction.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] Noyori asymmetric hydrogenation is the asymmetric reduction of β-keto-esters.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] With aqueous p*K*a values of around 16–19, alcohols are, in general, slightly weaker acids than water.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] With strong bases such as sodium hydride or sodium they form salts called *alkoxides*, with the general formula RO−M+ (where R is an alkyl and M is a metal).
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] The acidity of alcohols is strongly affected by solvation.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] In the gas phase, alcohols are more acidic than in water.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] In DMSO, alcohols (and water) have a p*K*a of around 29–32.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] As a consequence, alkoxides (and hydroxide) are powerful bases and nucleophiles (e.g., for the Williamson ether synthesis) in this solvent.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] In particular, RO− or HO− in DMSO can be used to generate significant equilibrium concentrations of acetylide ions through the deprotonation of alkynes (see Favorskii reaction).
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] Tertiary alcohols react with hydrochloric acid to produce tertiary alkyl chloride.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] Primary and secondary alcohols are converted to the corresponding chlorides using thionyl chloride and various phosphorus chloride reagents.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] In the Barton–McCombie deoxygenation an alcohol is deoxygenated to an alkane with tributyltin hydride or a trimethylborane-water complex in a radical substitution reaction.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] Meanwhile, the oxygen atom has lone pairs of nonbonded electrons that render it weakly basic in the presence of strong acids such as sulfuric acid.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] Upon treatment with strong acids, alcohols undergo the E1 elimination reaction to produce alkenes.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] The reaction, in general, obeys Zaytsev's rule, which states that the most stable (usually the most substituted) alkene is formed.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] Tertiary alcohols are eliminated easily at just above room temperature, but primary alcohols require a higher temperature.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] A more controlled elimination reaction requires the formation of the xanthate ester.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] Tertiary alcohols react with strong acids to generate carbocations.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] The reaction is related to their dehydration, e.g. isobutylene from *tert*-butyl alcohol.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] A special kind of dehydration reaction involves triphenylmethanol and especially its amine-substituted derivatives.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] When treated with acid, these alcohols lose water to give stable carbocations, which are commercial dyes.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] Alcohol and carboxylic acids react in the so-called Fischer esterification.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] Other types of ester are prepared in a similar manner−for example, tosyl (tosylate) esters are made by reaction of the alcohol with 4-toluenesulfonyl chloride in pyridine.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] Primary alcohols (R−CH2OH) can be oxidized either to aldehydes (R−CHO) or to carboxylic acids (R−CO2H).
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] The oxidation of secondary alcohols (R1R2CH−OH) normally terminates at the ketone (R1R2C=O) stage.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] Tertiary alcohols (R1R2R3C−OH) are resistant to oxidation.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] The direct oxidation of primary alcohols to carboxylic acids normally proceeds via the corresponding aldehyde, which is transformed via an *aldehyde hydrate* (R−CH(OH)2) by reaction with water before it can be further oxidized to the carboxylic acid.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] Reagents useful for the transformation of primary alcohols to aldehydes are normally also suitable for the oxidation of secondary alcohols to ketones.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] These include Collins reagent and Dess–Martin periodinane.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-chemistry] The direct oxidation of primary alcohols to carboxylic acids can be carried out using potassium permanganate or the Jones reagent.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] Various alcohols are used as fuel for internal combustion engines.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] The first four aliphatic alcohols (methanol, ethanol, propanol, and butanol) are of interest as fuels because they can be synthesized chemically or biologically, and they have characteristics which allow them to be used in internal combustion engines.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] The general chemical formula for alcohol fuel is **CnH2n+1OH**.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] Most methanol is produced from natural gas, although it can be produced from biomass using very similar chemical processes.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] Ethanol is commonly produced from biological material through fermentation processes.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] Biobutanol has the advantage in combustion engines in that its energy density is closer to gasoline than the simpler alcohols (while still retaining over 25% higher octane rating); however, biobutanol is currently more difficult to produce than ethanol or methanol.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] When obtained from biological materials and/or biological processes, they are known as **bioalcohols** (e.g.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] There is no chemical difference between biologically produced and chemically produced alcohols.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] One advantage shared by the four major alcohol fuels is their high octane rating.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] Methanol and ethanol can both be derived from fossil fuels, biomass, or from carbon dioxide and water.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] Ethanol has most commonly been produced through fermentation of sugars, and methanol has most commonly been produced from synthesis gas, but there are more modern ways to obtain these fuels.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] Enzymes can be used instead of fermentation.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] Methanol is the simpler molecule, and ethanol can be made from methanol.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] Methanol can be produced industrially from nearly any biomass, including animal waste, or from carbon dioxide and water or steam by first converting the biomass to synthesis gas in a gasifier.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] It can also be produced in a laboratory using electrolysis or enzymes.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] As a fuel, methanol and ethanol both have advantages and disadvantages over fuels such as petrol (gasoline) and diesel fuel.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] In spark ignition engines, both alcohols can run at much higher exhaust gas recirculation rates and with higher compression ratios.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] Both alcohols have a high octane rating, with ethanol at 109 RON (Research Octane Number), 90 MON (Motor Octane Number), (which equates to 99.5 AKI) and methanol at 109 RON, 89 MON (which equates to 99 AKI).
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] Note that AKI refers to 'Anti-Knock Index' which averages the RON and MON ratings (RON+MON)/2, and is used on U.S. gas station pumps.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] Ordinary European petrol is typically 95 RON, 85 MON, equal to 90 AKI.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] As a compression ignition engine fuel, both alcohols create very few particulates, but their low cetane number means that an ignition improver like glycol must be mixed into the fuel at approx.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] When used in spark ignition engines alcohols have the potential to reduce NOx, CO, HC and particulates.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] A test with E85 fueled Chevrolet Luminas showed that NMHC went down by 20-22%, NOx by 25-32% and CO by 12-24% compared to reformulated gasoline.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] Toxic emissions of benzene and 1,3-butadiene also decreased while aldehyde emissions increased, acetaldehyde in particular.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] Tailpipe emissions of CO2 also decrease due to the lower carbon-to-hydrogen ratio of these alcohols, and improved engine efficiency.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] Methanol and ethanol fuels contain soluble and insoluble contaminants.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] Halide ions, which are soluble contaminants, such as chloride ions, have a large effect on the corrosivity of alcohol fuels.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] Halide ions increase corrosion in two ways: they chemically attack passivating oxide films on several metals causing pitting corrosion, and they increase the conductivity of the fuel.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] Increased electrical conductivity promotes electrical, galvanic and ordinary corrosion in the fuel system.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] Soluble contaminants such as aluminum hydroxide, itself a product of corrosion by halide ions, clog the fuel system over time.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] To prevent corrosion the fuel system must be made of suitable materials, electrical wires must be properly insulated and the fuel level sensor must be of pulse and hold type magneto resistive or other similar non-contact type.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] In addition, high quality alcohol should have a low concentration of contaminants and have a suitable corrosion inhibitor added.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] Scientific evidence reveals that water is an inhibitor for corrosion by ethanol.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] The experiments are done with E50, which is more aggressive and speeds up the corrosion effect.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] It is very clear that by increasing the amount of water in fuel ethanol one can reduce corrosion.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] At 2% or 20,000 ppm water in the ethanol fuel the corrosion stopped.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] In line with the observations in Japan, hydrous ethanol is known to be less corrosive than anhydrous ethanol.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] The reaction mechanism is 3 EtOH + Al -> Al(OEt)3 + 3⁄2 H2 at lower-mid blends.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] When enough water is present in the fuel, aluminum will react preferably with water to produce Al2O3, repairing the protective aluminum oxide layer.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] The aluminum alkoxide does not make a tight oxide layer; water is essential to repair the holes in the oxide layer.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] Methanol and ethanol are incompatible with some polymers.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] The alcohol reacts with the polymers causing swelling, and over time oxygen breaks down the carbon-carbon bonds in the polymer causing a reduction in tensile strength.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] For the past few decades though, most cars have been designed to tolerate up to 10% ethanol (E10) without problem.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] This includes both fuel system compatibility and lambda compensation of fuel delivery with fuel injection engines featuring closed loop lambda control.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] In some engines ethanol may degrade some compositions of plastic or rubber fuel delivery components designed for conventional petrol, and also be unable to lambda compensate the fuel properly.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] "FlexFuel" vehicles have upgraded fuel system and engine components which are designed for long life using E85 or M85, and the ECU can adapt to any fuel blend between gasoline and E85 or M85.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] Typical upgrades include modifications to: fuel tanks, fuel tank electrical wiring, fuel pumps, fuel filters, fuel lines, filler tubes, fuel level sensors, fuel injectors, seals, fuel rails, fuel pressure regulators, valve seats and inlet valves.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] "Total Flex" autos destined for the Brazilian market can use E100 (100% ethanol).
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] One liter of ethanol releases 21.1 MJ in combustion, a liter of methanol 15.8 MJ and a liter of gasoline approximately 32.6 MJ.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] In other words, for the same energy content as one liter or one gallon of gasoline, one needs 1.6 liters/gallons of ethanol and 2.1 liters/gallons of methanol.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] The raw energy-per-volume numbers produce misleading fuel consumption numbers, however, because alcohol-fueled engines can be made substantially more energy-efficient.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] A larger percentage of the energy released by combustion of a liter of alcohol fuel can be converted to useful work.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] This difference in efficiency can partially or totally balance out the energy density difference, depending on the particular engines being compared.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] Methanol fuel has been proposed as a future biofuel, often as an alternative to the hydrogen economy.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] Methanol has a long history as a racing fuel.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] Early Grand Prix Racing used blended mixtures as well as pure methanol.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] The fuel was primarily used in North America after the war.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] However, methanol for racing purposes has largely been based on methanol produced from syngas derived from natural gas and therefore this methanol would not be considered a biofuel.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] Methanol is a possible biofuel, however, when the syngas is derived from biomass.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] In theory, methanol can also be produced from sustainably sourced biomass and ultimately carbon dioxide, and by hydrogen electrolysis using nuclear power, geothermal power or some other renewable energy source (see Carbon Recycling International).
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] Compared to bioethanol, the primary advantage of methanol biofuel is its much greater well-to-wheel efficiency.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] This is particularly relevant in temperate climates where fertilizers are needed to grow sugar or starch crops to make ethanol, whereas methanol can be produced from unfertilized lignocellulose (woody) biomass.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] Ethanol is already being used extensively as a fuel additive, and the use of ethanol fuel alone or as part of a mix with gasoline is increasing.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] Compared to methanol its primary advantage is that it is less corrosive and non-toxic, although the fuel will produce some toxic exhaust emissions.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] Since 2007, IndyCar has used ethanol as its exclusive fuel, after 40 years of using methanol.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] Since September 2007 petrol stations in NSW, Australia have been mandated to supply all their petrol with 2% ethanol content.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] Propanol and butanol are considerably less toxic and less volatile than methanol.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] In particular, butanol has a high flash point of 35 °C, which is a benefit for fire safety, but may be a difficulty for starting engines in cold weather.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] The concept of flash point is, however, not directly applicable to engines as the compression of the air in the cylinder means that the temperature is several hundred degrees Celsius before ignition takes place.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] This organism also dies when the butanol content of whatever it is fermenting rises to 2%.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] For comparison, yeast dies when the ethanol content of its feedstock hits 14%.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] Specialized strains can tolerate even greater ethanol concentrations - so-called turbo yeast can withstand up to 16% ethanol.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] However, if ordinary Saccharomyces yeast can be modified to improve its ethanol resistance, scientists may yet one day produce a strain of the Weizmann organism with a butanol resistance higher than the natural boundary of 7%.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] This would be useful because butanol has a higher combustion energy density than ethanol, and because waste fibre left over from sugar crops used to make ethanol could be made into butanol, raising the alcohol yield of fuel crops without requiring more crops to be planted.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] Despite these drawbacks, DuPont and BP have recently announced that they are jointly to build a small scale butanol fuel demonstration plant alongside the large bioethanol plant they are jointly developing with Associated British Foods.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] The company Energy Environment International developed a method for producing butanol from biomass, which involves the use of two separate micro-organisms in sequence to minimize production of acetone and ethanol byproducts.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] The Swiss company Butalco GmbH uses a special technology to modify yeasts in order to produce butanol instead of ethanol.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] Yeasts as production organisms for butanol have decisive advantages compared to bacteria.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] The 3-carbon alcohol, propanol (C3H7OH), is not often used as a direct fuel source for petrol engines (unlike ethanol, methanol and butanol), with most being directed into use as a solvent.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] However, it is used as a source of hydrogen in some types of fuel cell; it can generate a higher voltage than methanol, which is the fuel of choice for most alcohol-based fuel cells.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] However, since propanol is harder to produce than methanol (biologically or from oil), methanol-utilizing fuel cells are preferred over those that utilize propanol.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] Brazil was until recently the largest producer of alcohol fuel in the world, typically fermenting ethanol from sugarcane.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] The country produces a total of 18 billion litres (4.8 billion gallons) annually, of which 3.5 billion liters are exported, 2 billion of them to the U.S.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] Alcohol cars debuted in the Brazilian market in 1979 and became quite popular because of a heavy subsidy, but in the 1980s prices rose and gasoline regained the leading market share.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] However, from 2003 on, alcohol has rapidly increased its market share once again because of new technologies involving flexible-fuel engines, called "Flex" or "Total Flex" by all major car manufacturers (Volkswagen, General Motors, Fiat, etc.).
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] "Flex" engines work with gasoline, alcohol or any mixture of both fuels.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] As of May 2009, more than 88% of new vehicles sold in Brazil are flex fuel.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] Because of the Brazilian leading production and technology, many countries became very interested in importing alcohol fuel and adopting the "Flex" vehicle concept.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] On March 7 of 2007, US president George W.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] Bush visited the city of São Paulo to sign agreements with Brazilian president Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva on importing alcohol and its technology as an alternative fuel.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] As early as 1935, China has made alcohol fuel powered cars.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] China has reported with a 70% methanol use to conventional gasoline an independence from crude oil.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] The National Committee of Planning and Action Coordination for Clean Automobile had listed key technologies related to alcohol/ether fuel and accelerated industrialization in its main agenda.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] Alcohol fuels had become part of five main alternative fuels, two of which were alcohols: methanol and ethanol.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] The United States at the end of 2007 was producing 26.9 billion litres (7 billion gallons) per year.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] E10 or Gasohol is commonly marketed in Delaware and E85 is found in many states, particularly in the Midwest where ethanol from corn is produced locally.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] Many states and municipalities have mandated that all gasoline fuel be blended with 10 percent alcohol (usually ethanol) during some or all of the year.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] This is to reduce pollution and allows these areas to comply with federal pollution limits.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] Because alcohol is partially oxygenated, it produces less overall pollution, including ozone.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] In some areas (California in particular) the regulations may also require other formulations or added chemicals that reduce pollution, but add complexity to the fuel distribution and increase the cost of the fuel.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] The first alcohol fuel in Japan began with **GAIAX** in 1999.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] GAIAX was developed in South Korea, and imported by Japan.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] Because GAIAX was not gasoline, it was a tax-free object of the gas tax of Japan.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] However, as a result, the use of GAIAX came to be considered an act of smuggling in Japan by the government and the petroleum industry.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] Retailing of GAIAX was done to avoid the tax evasion criticism by independently paying the diesel fuel tax in the legal system regulations.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] Accidental vehicle fires where GAIAX was being refueled began to be reported in around 2000 when the tax evasion discussion had almost ended.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] The car industry in Japan criticized GAIAX, saying that "fires broke out because high density alcohol had corroded the fuel pipes".
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] GAIAX was named a "high density alcohol fuel", and a campaign was executed to exclude it from the market long term.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] Finally, the Ministry of Economy, Trade and Industry also joined this campaign.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] The gasoline quality method was revised under the pretext of safety concerns in 2003.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] This prohibited the manufacturing and sale of "High density alcohol fuel", and added a substantial GAIAX sales ban.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] By revising the law, fuel manufacturers are prohibited from adding 3% or more alcohol to gasoline.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] This revision to the law is grounds not to be able to sell alcohol fuel greater than E3 in Japan.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] The petroleum industry in Japan is now proceeding with research and development of an original alcohol fuel that differs from GAIAX.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] However, the commercial manufacture and sale of any new fuel may be barred by existing laws that currently exclude GAIAX from the market.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alcohol-fuel] Moreover, the strong aversion by the Japanese consumer to a high density alcohol fuel of any type may prevent commercial success of any new fuel.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] In 1942, Harder and Von Witsch were the first to propose that microalgae be grown as a source of lipids for food or fuel.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Following World War II, research began in the US, Germany, Japan, England, and Israel on culturing techniques and engineering systems for growing microalgae on larger scales, particularly species in the genus *Chlorella*.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Aach showed that *Chlorella pyrenoidosa* could be induced via nitrogen starvation to accumulate as much as 70% of its dry weight as lipids.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Since the need for alternative transportation fuel had subsided after World War II, research at this time focused on culturing algae as a food source or, in some cases, for wastewater treatment.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Interest in the application of algae for biofuels was rekindled during the oil embargo and oil price surges of the 1970s, leading the US Department of Energy to initiate the Aquatic Species Program in 1978.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] The Aquatic Species Program spent $25 million over 18 years to develop liquid transportation fuel from algae that would be price-competitive with petroleum-derived fuels.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] The research program focused on microalgae cultivation in open outdoor ponds, systems that are low in cost but vulnerable to environmental disturbances like temperature swings and biological invasions.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Among the program's most significant findings were that rapid growth and high lipid production were "mutually exclusive" since the former required high nutrients and the latter required low nutrients.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] The final report suggested that genetic engineering may be necessary to be able to overcome this and other natural limitations of algal strains and that the ideal species might vary with place and season.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Although it was successfully demonstrated that large-scale production of algae for fuel in outdoor ponds was feasible, the program failed to do so at a cost that would be competitive with petroleum, especially as oil prices sank in the 1990s.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Even in the best-case scenario, it was estimated that unextracted algal oil would cost $59–186 per barrel, while petroleum cost less than $20 per barrel in 1995.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Therefore, under budget pressure in 1996, the Aquatic Species Program was abandoned.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Other contributions to algal biofuels research have come indirectly from projects focusing on different applications of algal cultures.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] For example, in the 1990s Japan's Research Institute of Innovative Technology for the Earth (RITE) implemented a research program with the goal of developing systems to fix CO 2 using microalgae.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Although the goal was not energy production, several studies produced by RITE demonstrated that algae could be grown using flue gas from power plants as a CO 2 source, an important development for algal biofuel research.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Other work focusing on harvesting hydrogen gas, methane, or ethanol from algae, as well as nutritional supplements and pharmaceutical compounds, has also helped inform research on biofuel production from algae.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Following the disbanding of the Aquatic Species Program in 1996, there was a relative lull in algal biofuel research.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Still, various projects were funded in the US by the Department of Energy, Department of Defense, National Science Foundation, Department of Agriculture, National Laboratories, state funding, and private funding, as well as in other countries.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] More recently, rising oil prices in the 2000s spurred a revival of interest in algal biofuels and US federal funding has increased, numerous research projects are being funded in Australia, New Zealand, Europe, the Middle East, and other parts of the world.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] In December 2022, ExxonMobil, the last large oil company to invest in algae biofuels, ended its research funding.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] In March 2023, researchers said that the commercialization of biofuels would require several billion dollars of funding, plus a long-term dedication to overcoming what appear to be fundamental biological limitations of wild organisms.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Algal oil is used as a source of fatty acid supplementation in food products, as it contains mono- and polyunsaturated fats, in particular EPA and DHA.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Its DHA content is roughly equivalent to that of salmon based fish oil.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Algae can be converted into various types of fuels, depending on the production technologies and the part of the cells used.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] The lipid, or oily part of the algae biomass can be extracted and converted into biodiesel through a process similar to that used for any other vegetable oil, or converted in a refinery into "drop-in" replacements for petroleum-based fuels.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Alternatively or following lipid extraction, the carbohydrate content of algae can be fermented into bioethanol or butanol fuel.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Biodiesel is a diesel fuel derived from animal or plant lipids (oils and fats).
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Studies have shown that some species of algae can produce 60% or more of their dry weight in the form of oil.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Because the cells grow in aqueous suspension, where they have more efficient access to water, CO 2 and dissolved nutrients, microalgae are capable of producing large amounts of biomass and usable oil in either high rate algal ponds or photobioreactors.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] This oil can then be turned into biodiesel which could be sold for use in automobiles.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Regional production of microalgae and processing into biofuels will provide economic benefits to rural communities.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] As they do not have to produce structural compounds such as cellulose for leaves, stems, or roots, and because they can be grown floating in a rich nutritional medium, microalgae can have faster growth rates than terrestrial crops.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Also, they can convert a much higher fraction of their biomass to oil than conventional crops, e.g.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] The per unit area yield of oil from algae is estimated to be from 58,700 to 136,900 L/ha/year, depending on lipid content, which is 10 to 23 times as high as the next highest yielding crop, oil palm, at 5 950 L/ha/year.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Department of Energy's Aquatic Species Program, 1978–1996, focused on biodiesel from microalgae.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] The final report suggested that biodiesel could be the only viable method by which to produce enough fuel to replace current world diesel usage.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] If algae-derived biodiesel were to replace the annual global production of 1.1bn tons of conventional diesel then a land mass of 57.3 million hectares would be required, which would be highly favorable compared to other biofuels.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Algae can be used to produce 'green diesel' (also known as renewable diesel, hydrotreating vegetable oil or hydrogen-derived renewable diesel) through a hydrotreating refinery process that breaks molecules down into shorter hydrocarbon chains used in diesel engines.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] It has the same chemical properties as petroleum-based diesel meaning that it does not require new engines, pipelines or infrastructure to distribute and use.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] It has yet to be produced at a cost that is competitive with petroleum.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] While hydrotreating is currently the most common pathway to produce fuel-like hydrocarbons via decarboxylation/decarbonylation, there is an alternative process offering a number of important advantages over hydrotreating.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] In this regard, the work of Crocker et al. and Lercher et al. is particularly noteworthy.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] For oil refining, research is underway for catalytic conversion of renewable fuels by decarboxylation.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] As the oxygen is present in crude oil at rather low levels, of the order of 0.5%, deoxygenation in petroleum refining is not of much concern, and no catalysts are specifically formulated for oxygenates hydrotreating.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Hence, one of the critical technical challenges to make the hydrodeoxygenation of algae oil process economically feasible is related to the research and development of effective catalysts.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Butanol can be made from algae or diatoms using only a solar powered biorefinery.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] This fuel has an energy density 10% less than gasoline, and greater than that of either ethanol or methanol.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] In most gasoline engines, butanol can be used in place of gasoline with no modifications.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] In several tests, butanol consumption is similar to that of gasoline, and when blended with gasoline, provides better performance and corrosion resistance than that of ethanol or E85.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] The green waste left over from the algae oil extraction can be used to produce butanol.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] In addition, it has been shown that macroalgae (seaweeds) can be fermented by bacteria of genus *Clostridia* to butanol and other solvents.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Transesterification of seaweed oil (into biodiesel) is also possible with species such as *Chaetomorpha linum*, *Ulva lactuca*, and *Enteromorpha compressa* (*Ulva*).
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Biogasoline is gasoline produced from biomass.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Like traditionally produced gasoline, it contains between 6 (hexane) and 12 (dodecane) carbon atoms per molecule and can be used in internal-combustion engines.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Biogas is composed mainly of methane (CH4) and carbon dioxide (CO2), with some traces of hydrogen sulphide, oxygen, nitrogen, and hydrogen.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Macroalgae has high methane production rate compared to plant biomass.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Biogas production from macroalgae is more technically viable compared to other fuels, but it is not economically viable due to the high cost of macroalgae feedstock.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Carbohydrate and protein in microalgae can be converted into biogas through anaerobic digestion, which includes hydrolysis, fermentation, and methanogenesis steps.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] The conversion of algal biomass into methane can potentially recover as much energy as it obtains, but it is more profitable when the algal lipid content is lower than 40%.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Biogas production from microalgae is relatively low because of the high ratio of protein in microalgae, but microalgae can be co-digested with high C/N ratio products such as wastepaper.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Another method to produce biogas is through gasification, where hydrocarbon is converted to syngas through a partial oxidation reaction at high temperature (typically 800 °C to 1000 °C).
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Gasification is usually performed with catalysts.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Uncatalyzed gasification requires temperature to be about 1300 °C.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Syngas can be burnt directly to produce energy or used a fuel in turbine engines.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] It can also be used as feedstock for other chemical productions.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Methane, the main constituent of natural gas, can be produced from algae by various methods, namely gasification, pyrolysis and anaerobic digestion.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] In gasification and pyrolysis methods methane is extracted under high temperature and pressure.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] A number of studies have successfully shown that biomass from microalgae can be converted into biogas via anaerobic digestion.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Therefore, in order to improve the overall energy balance of microalgae cultivation operations, it has been proposed to recover the energy contained in waste biomass via anaerobic digestion to methane for generating electricity.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] The Algenol system which is being commercialized by BioFields in Puerto Libertad, Sonora, Mexico utilizes seawater and industrial exhaust to produce ethanol.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Porphyridium cruentum also have shown to be potentially suitable for ethanol production due to its capacity for accumulating large amount of carbohydrates.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Trials of using algae as biofuel were carried out by Lufthansa and Virgin Atlantic as early as 2008, although there is little evidence that using algae is a reasonable source for jet biofuels.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] By 2015, cultivation of fatty acid methyl esters and alkenones from the algae, *Isochrysis*, was under research as a possible jet biofuel feedstock.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] In May 2022, scientists at University of Cambridge announced they created an algae energy harvester, that uses natural sunlight to power a small microprocessor, initially powering the processor for six months, and then kept going for a full year.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] The device, which is about the size of AA battery, is a small container with water and blue green algae.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] The device does not generate a huge amount of power, but it can be used for Internet of Things devices, eliminating the need for traditional batteries such as lithium-ion batteries.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] The goal is to have more an environmentally friendly power source that can be used in remote areas.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Research into algae for the mass-production of oil focuses mainly on microalgae (organisms capable of photosynthesis that are less than 0.4 mm in diameter, including the diatoms and cyanobacteria) as opposed to macroalgae, such as seaweed.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] The preference for microalgae has come about due largely to their less complex structure, fast growth rates, and high oil-content (for some species).
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] However, some research is being done into using seaweeds for biofuels, probably due to the high availability of this resource.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] The amount of oil each strain of algae produces varies widely.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] In addition, due to its high growth-rate, *Ulva* has been investigated as a fuel for use in the *SOFT cycle*, (SOFT stands for Solar Oxygen Fuel Turbine), a closed-cycle power-generation system suitable for use in arid, subtropical regions.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Other species used include *Clostridium saccharoperbutylacetonicum*, *Sargassum*, *Gracilaria*, *Prymnesium parvum*, and *Euglena gracilis*.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Light is what algae primarily need for growth as it is the most limiting factor.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Many companies are investing for developing systems and technologies for providing artificial light.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] One of them is OriginOil that has developed a Helix BioReactorTM that features a rotating vertical shaft with low-energy lights arranged in a helix pattern.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Water temperature also influences the metabolic and reproductive rates of algae.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Although most algae grow at low rate when the water temperature gets lower, the biomass of algal communities can get large due to the absence of grazing organisms.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] The modest increases in water current velocity may also affect rates of algae growth since the rate of nutrient uptake and boundary layer diffusion increases with current velocity.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Other than light and water, phosphorus, nitrogen, and certain micronutrients are also useful and essential in growing algae.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Nitrogen and phosphorus are the two most significant nutrients required for algal productivity, but other nutrients such as carbon and silica are additionally required.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Of the nutrients required, phosphorus is one of the most essential ones as it is used in numerous metabolic processes.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] The microalgae *D. tertiolecta* was analyzed to see which nutrient affects its growth the most.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] The concentrations of phosphorus (P), iron (Fe), cobalt (Co), zinc (Zn), manganese (Mn) and molybdenum (Mo), magnesium (Mg), calcium (Ca), silicon (Si) and sulfur (S) concentrations were measured daily using inductively coupled plasma (ICP) analysis.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Among all these elements being measured, phosphorus resulted in the most dramatic decrease, with a reduction of 84% over the course of the culture.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] This result indicates that phosphorus, in the form of phosphate, is required in high amounts by all organisms for metabolism.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] There are two enrichment media that have been extensively used to grow most species of algae: Walne medium and the Guillard's F/2 medium.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] These commercially available nutrient solutions may reduce time for preparing all the nutrients required to grow algae.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] However, due to their complexity in the process of generation and high cost, they are not used for large-scale culture operations.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Therefore, enrichment media used for mass production of algae contain only the most important nutrients with agriculture-grade fertilizers rather than laboratory-grade fertilizers.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Algae grow much faster than food crops, and can produce hundreds of times more oil per unit area than conventional crops such as rapeseed, palms, soybeans, or jatropha.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] As algae have a harvesting cycle of 1–10 days, their cultivation permits several harvests in a very short time-frame, a strategy differing from that associated with annual crops.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] In addition, algae can be grown on land unsuitable for terrestrial crops, including arid land and land with excessively saline soil, minimizing competition with agriculture.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Most research on algae cultivation has focused on growing algae in clean but expensive photobioreactors, or in open ponds, which are cheap to maintain but prone to contamination.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] The lack of equipment and structures needed to begin growing algae in large quantities has inhibited widespread mass-production of algae for biofuel production.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Maximum use of existing agriculture processes and hardware is the goal.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Closed systems (not exposed to open air) avoid the problem of contamination by other organisms blown in by the air.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] The problem of a closed system is finding a cheap source of sterile CO 2.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Several experimenters have found the CO 2 from a smokestack works well for growing algae.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] For reasons of economy, some experts think that algae farming for biofuels will have to be done as part of cogeneration, where it can make use of waste heat and help soak up pollution.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] To produce micro-algae at large-scale under controlled environment using PBR system, strategies such as light guides, sparger, and PBR construction materials required should be well considered.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Most companies pursuing algae as a source of biofuels pump nutrient-rich water through plastic or borosilicate glass tubes (called "bioreactors" ) that are exposed to sunlight (and so-called photobioreactors or PBR).
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Running a PBR is more difficult than using an open pond, and costlier, but may provide a higher level of control and productivity.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] In addition, a photobioreactor can be integrated into a closed loop cogeneration system much more easily than ponds or other methods.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Open pond systems consist of simple in ground ponds, which are often mixed by a paddle wheel.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] These systems have low power requirements, operating costs, and capital costs when compared to closed loop photobioreactor systems.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Nearly all commercial algae producers for high value algal products utilize open pond systems.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] The Algae scrubber is a system designed primarily for cleaning nutrients and pollutants out of water using algal turfs.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] An algal turf scrubber (ATS) mimics the algal turfs of a natural coral reef by taking in nutrient rich water from waste streams or natural water sources, and pulsing it over a sloped surface.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] This surface is coated with a rough plastic membrane or a screen, which allows naturally occurring algal spores to settle and colonize the surface.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Once the algae has been established, it can be harvested every 5–15 days, and can produce 18 metric tons of algal biomass per hectare per year.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] In contrast to other methods, which focus primarily on a single high yielding species of algae, this method focuses on naturally occurring polycultures of algae.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] As such, the lipid content of the algae in an ATS system is usually lower, which makes it more suitable for a fermented fuel product, such as ethanol, methane, or butanol.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Conversely, the harvested algae could be treated with a hydrothermal liquefaction process, which would make possible biodiesel, gasoline, and jet fuel production.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] There are three major advantages of ATS over other systems.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] The first advantage is documented higher productivity over open pond systems.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] The second is lower operating and fuel production costs.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] The third is the elimination of contamination issues due to the reliance on naturally occurring algae species.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] The projected costs for energy production in an ATS system are $0.75/kg, compared to a photobioreactor which would cost $3.50/kg.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] After harvesting the algae, the biomass is typically processed in a series of steps, which can differ based on the species and desired product; this is an active area of research and also is the bottleneck of this technology: the cost of extraction is higher than those obtained.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] One of the solutions is to use filter feeders to "eat" them.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Improved animals can provide both foods and fuels.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] An alternative method to extract the algae is to grow the algae with specific types of fungi.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] This causes bio-flocculation of the algae which allows for easier extraction.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Often, the algae is dehydrated, and then a solvent such as hexane is used to extract energy-rich compounds like triglycerides from the dried material.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Then, the extracted compounds can be processed into fuel using standard industrial procedures.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] For example, the extracted triglycerides are reacted with methanol to create biodiesel via transesterification.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] The unique composition of fatty acids of each species influences the quality of the resulting biodiesel and thus must be taken into account when selecting algal species for feedstock.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] An alternative approach called Hydrothermal liquefaction employs a continuous process that subjects harvested wet algae to high temperatures and pressures—350 °C (662 °F) and 3,000 pounds per square inch (21,000 kPa).
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Products include crude oil, which can be further refined into aviation fuel, gasoline, or diesel fuel using one or many upgrading processes.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] The test process can convert about 79 percent of the algae's carbon into fuel.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Nutrients like nitrogen (N), phosphorus (P), and potassium (K), are important for plant growth and are essential parts of fertilizer.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Silica and iron, as well as several trace elements, may also be considered important marine nutrients as the lack of one can limit the growth of, or productivity in, an area.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Bubbling CO 2 through algal cultivation systems can greatly increase productivity and yield (up to a saturation point).
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Typically, about 1.8 tonnes of CO 2 will be utilised per tonne of algal biomass (dry) produced, though this varies with algae species.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] The Glenturret Distillery in Perthshire percolate CO 2 made during the whisky distillation through a microalgae bioreactor.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Each tonne of microalgae absorbs two tonnes of CO 2.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Scottish Bioenergy, who run the project, sell the microalgae as high value, protein-rich food for fisheries.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] In the future, they will use the algae residues to produce renewable energy through anaerobic digestion.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Nitrogen is a valuable substrate that can be utilized in algal growth.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Various sources of nitrogen can be used as a nutrient for algae, with varying capacities.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Nitrate was found to be the preferred source of nitrogen, in regards to amount of biomass grown.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Urea is a readily available source that shows comparable results, making it an economical substitute for nitrogen source in large scale culturing of algae.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Despite the clear increase in growth in comparison to a nitrogen-less medium, it has been shown that alterations in nitrogen levels affect lipid content within the algal cells.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] In one study nitrogen deprivation for 72 hours caused the total fatty acid content (on a per cell basis) to increase by 2.4-fold.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] 65% of the total fatty acids were esterified to triacylglycerides in oil bodies, when compared to the initial culture, indicating that the algal cells utilized de novo synthesis of fatty acids.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] It is vital for the lipid content in algal cells to be of high enough quantity, while maintaining adequate cell division times, so parameters that can maximize both are under investigation.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] A possible nutrient source is wastewater from the treatment of sewage, agricultural, or flood plain run-off, all currently major pollutants and health risks.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] However, this waste water cannot feed algae directly and must first be processed by bacteria, through anaerobic digestion.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] If waste water is not processed before it reaches the algae, it will contaminate the algae in the reactor, and at the very least, kill much of the desired algae strain.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] In biogas facilities, organic waste is often converted to a mixture of carbon dioxide, methane, and organic fertilizer.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Organic fertilizer that comes out of the digester is liquid, and nearly suitable for algae growth, but it must first be cleaned and sterilized.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] The utilization of wastewater and ocean water instead of freshwater is strongly advocated due to the continuing depletion of freshwater resources.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] However, heavy metals, trace metals, and other contaminants in wastewater can decrease the ability of cells to produce lipids biosynthetically and also impact various other workings in the machinery of cells.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] The same is true for ocean water, but the contaminants are found in different concentrations.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Thus, agricultural-grade fertilizer is the preferred source of nutrients, but heavy metals are again a problem, especially for strains of algae that are susceptible to these metals.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] In open pond systems the use of strains of algae that can deal with high concentrations of heavy metals could prevent other organisms from infesting these systems.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] In some instances it has even been shown that strains of algae can remove over 90% of nickel and zinc from industrial wastewater in relatively short periods of time.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] In comparison with terrestrial-based biofuel crops such as corn or soybeans, microalgal production results in a much less significant land footprint due to the higher oil productivity from the microalgae than all other oil crops.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Algae can also be grown on marginal lands useless for ordinary crops and with low conservation value, and can use water from salt aquifers that is not useful for agriculture or drinking.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Algae can also grow on the surface of the ocean in bags or floating screens.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Thus microalgae could provide a source of clean energy with little impact on the provisioning of adequate food and water or the conservation of biodiversity.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Algae cultivation also requires no external subsidies of insecticides or herbicides, removing any risk of generating associated pesticide waste streams.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] In addition, algal biofuels are much less toxic, and degrade far more readily than petroleum-based fuels.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] However, due to the flammable nature of any combustible fuel, there is potential for some environmental hazards if ignited or spilled, as may occur in a train derailment or a pipeline leak.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] This hazard is reduced compared to fossil fuels, due to the ability for algal biofuels to be produced in a much more localized manner, and due to the lower toxicity overall, but the hazard is still there nonetheless.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Therefore, algal biofuels should be treated in a similar manner to petroleum fuels in transportation and use, with sufficient safety measures in place at all times.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Studies have determined that replacing fossil fuels with renewable energy sources, such as biofuels, have the capability of reducing CO 2 emissions by up to 80%.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] An algae-based system could capture approximately 80% of the CO 2 emitted from a power plant when sunlight is available.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Although this CO 2 will later be released into the atmosphere when the fuel is burned, this CO 2 would have entered the atmosphere regardless.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] The possibility of reducing total CO 2 emissions therefore lies in the prevention of the release of CO 2 from fossil fuels.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Since terrestrial plant sources of biofuel production simply do not have the production capacity to meet current energy requirements, microalgae may be one of the only options to approach complete replacement of fossil fuels.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] However, current algae biofuels are often much less efficient than other biofuels.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Microalgae production also includes the ability to use saline waste or waste CO 2 streams as an energy source.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] This opens a new strategy to produce biofuel in conjunction with waste water treatment, while being able to produce clean water as a byproduct.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] When used in a microalgal bioreactor, harvested microalgae will capture significant quantities of organic compounds as well as heavy metal contaminants absorbed from wastewater streams that would otherwise be directly discharged into surface and ground-water.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Moreover, this process also allows the recovery of phosphorus from waste, which is an essential but scarce element in nature – the reserves of which are estimated to have depleted in the last 50 years.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Another possibility is the use of algae production systems to clean up non-point source pollution, in a system known as an algal turf scrubber (ATS).
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] This has been demonstrated to reduce nitrogen and phosphorus levels in rivers and other large bodies of water affected by eutrophication, and systems are being built that will be capable of processing up to 110 million liters of water per day.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] ATS can also be used for treating point source pollution, such as the waste water mentioned above, or in treating livestock effluent.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Nearly all research in algal biofuels has focused on culturing single species, or monocultures, of microalgae.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] However, ecological theory and empirical studies have demonstrated that plant and algae polycultures, i.e. groups of multiple species, tend to produce larger yields than monocultures.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Experiments have also shown that more diverse aquatic microbial communities tend to be more stable through time than less diverse communities.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Recent studies found that polycultures of microalgae produced significantly higher lipid yields than monocultures.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Polycultures also tend to be more resistant to pest and disease outbreaks, as well as invasion by other plants or algae.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Thus culturing microalgae in polyculture may not only increase yields and stability of yields of biofuel, but also reduce the environmental impact of an algal biofuel industry.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] There is clearly a demand for sustainable biofuel production, but whether a particular biofuel will be used ultimately depends not on sustainability but cost efficiency.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Therefore, research is focusing on cutting the cost of algal biofuel production to the point where it can compete with conventional petroleum.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] The production of several products from algae has been mentioned as the most important factor for making algae production economically viable.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Other factors are the improving of the solar energy to biomass conversion efficiency (currently 3%, but 5 to 7% is theoretically attainable) and making the oil extraction from the algae easier.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] where: C(algal oil) is the price of microalgal oil in dollars per gallon and C(petroleum) is the price of crude oil in dollars per barrel.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] This equation assumes that algal oil has roughly 80% of the caloric energy value of crude petroleum.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] The IEA estimated in 2017 that algal biomass can be produced for a little as $0.54/kg in open pond in a warm climate to $10.20/kg in photobioreactors in cooler climates.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Assuming that the biomass contains 30% oil by weight, the cost of biomass for providing a liter of oil would be approximately $1.40 ($5.30/gal) and $1.81 ($6.85/gal) for photobioreactors and raceways, respectively.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Oil recovered from the lower cost biomass produced in photobioreactors is estimated to cost $2.80/L, assuming the recovery process contributes 50% to the cost of the final recovered oil.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] If existing algae projects can achieve biodiesel production price targets of less than $1 per gallon, the United States may realize its goal of replacing up to 20% of transport fuels by 2020 by using environmentally and economically sustainable fuels from algae production.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Whereas technical problems, such as harvesting, are being addressed successfully by the industry, the high up-front investment of algae-to-biofuels facilities is seen by many as a major obstacle to the success of this technology.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] As of 2007, only few studies on the economic viability were publicly available, and must often rely on the little data (often only engineering estimates) available in the public domain.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Dmitrov examined the GreenFuel's photobioreactor and estimated that algae oil would only be competitive at an oil price of $800 per barrel.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] A study by Alabi et al. examined raceways, photobioreactors and anaerobic fermenters to make biofuels from algae and found that photobioreactors are too expensive to make biofuels.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Raceways might be cost-effective in warm climates with very low labor costs, and fermenters may become cost-effective subsequent to significant process improvements.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] The group found that capital cost, labor cost and operational costs (fertilizer, electricity, etc.) by themselves are too high for algae biofuels to be cost-competitive with conventional fuels.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Similar results were found by others, suggesting that unless new, cheaper ways of harnessing algae for biofuels production are found, their great technical potential may never become economically accessible.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Teixeira demonstrated a new reaction and proposed a process for harvesting and extracting raw materials for biofuel and chemical production that requires a fraction of the energy of current methods, while extracting all cell constituents.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] A 2022 study stated that selling fuel from commercially refining biofuel was not feasible due to technological limitations and high costs.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] The study found that byproducts would require a selling price of $899/ton of residual solids in order to support a competitive price of $2.50 per gallon gasoline equivalent, using the method of converting proteins and carbohydrates into mixed alcohols.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Comparatively, the study found converting proteins and carbohydrates into hydrocarbons to require a higher selling price $1033/ton of residual solids in order to be economically feasible.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Many of the byproducts produced in the processing of microalgae can be used in various applications, many of which have a longer history of production than algal biofuel.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Some of the products not used in the production of biofuel include natural dyes and pigments, antioxidants, and other high-value bio-active compounds.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] These chemicals and excess biomass have found numerous use in other industries.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] For example, the dyes and oils have found a place in cosmetics, commonly as thickening and water-binding agents.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Discoveries within the pharmaceutical industry include antibiotics and antifungals derived from microalgae, as well as natural health products, which have been growing in popularity over the past few decades.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] For instance *Spirulina* contains numerous polyunsaturated fats (Omega 3 and 6), amino acids, and vitamins, as well as pigments that may be beneficial, such as beta-carotene and chlorophyll.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] One of the main advantages that using microalgae as the feedstock when compared to more traditional crops is that it can be grown much more easily.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Algae can be grown in land that would not be considered suitable for the growth of the regularly used crops.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] In addition to this, wastewater that would normally hinder plant growth has been shown to be very effective in growing algae.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Because of this, algae can be grown without taking up arable land that would otherwise be used for producing food crops, and the better resources can be reserved for normal crop production.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Microalgae also require fewer resources to grow and little attention is needed, allowing the growth and cultivation of algae to be a very passive process.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Many traditional feedstocks for biodiesel, such as corn and palm, are also used as feed for livestock on farms, as well as a valuable source of food for humans.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Because of this, using them as biofuel reduces the amount of food available for both, resulting in an increased cost for both the food and the fuel produced.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Using algae as a source of biodiesel can alleviate this problem in a number of ways.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] First, algae is not used as a primary food source for humans, meaning that it can be used solely for fuel and there would be little impact in the food industry.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Second, many of the waste-product extracts produced during the processing of algae for biofuel can be used as a sufficient animal feed.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] This is an effective way to minimize waste and a much cheaper alternative to the more traditional corn- or grain-based feeds.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Growing algae as a source of biofuel has also been shown to have numerous environmental benefits, and has presented itself as a much more environmentally friendly alternative to current biofuels.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] For one, it is able to utilize run-off, water contaminated with fertilizers and other nutrients that are a by-product of farming, as its primary source of water and nutrients.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Because of this, it prevents this contaminated water from mixing with the lakes and rivers that currently supply our drinking water.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] In addition to this, the ammonia, nitrates, and phosphates that would normally render the water unsafe actually serve as excellent nutrients for the algae, meaning that fewer resources are needed to grow the algae.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Many algae species used in biodiesel production are excellent bio-fixers, meaning they are able to remove carbon dioxide from the atmosphere to use as a form of energy for themselves.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Because of this, they have found use in industry as a way to treat flue gases and reduce GHG emissions.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] The process of microalgae cultivation is highly water-intensive.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Life cycle studies estimated that the production of 1 liter of microalgae based biodiesel requires between 607 and 1944 liters of water.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] That said, abundant wastewater and/or seawater, which also contain various nutrients, can theoretically be used for this purpose instead of freshwater.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Algae biodiesel is still a fairly new technology.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Despite the fact that research began over 30 years ago, it was put on hold during the mid-1990s, mainly due to a lack of funding and a relatively low petroleum cost.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] For the next few years algae biofuels saw little attention; it was not until the gas peak of the early 2000s that it eventually had a revitalization in the search for alternative fuel sources.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Increasing interest in seaweed farming for carbon sequestration, eutrophication reduction and production of food has resulted in the creation of commercial seaweed cultivation since 2017.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Reductions in the cost of cultivation and harvesting as well as the development of commercial industry will improve the economics of macroalgae biofuels.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Climate change has created a proliferation of brown macroalgae mats, which wash up on the shores of the Caribbean.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Currently these mats are disposed of but there is interest in developing them into a feedstock for biofuel production.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] The biodiesel produced from the processing of microalgae differs from other forms of biodiesel in the content of polyunsaturated fats.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Polyunsaturated fats are known for their ability to retain fluidity at lower temperatures.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] While this may seem like an advantage in production during the colder temperatures of the winter, the polyunsaturated fats result in lower stability during regular seasonal temperatures.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Numerous policies have been put in place since the 1975 oil crisis in order to promote the use of Renewable Fuels in the United States, Canada and Europe.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] In Canada, these included the implementation of excise taxes exempting propane and natural gas which was extended to ethanol made from biomass and methanol in 1992.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Policies in the United States have included a decrease in the subsidies provided by the federal and state governments to the oil industry which have usually included $2.84 billion.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] This is more than what is actually set aside for the biofuel industry.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] The measure was discussed at the G20 in Pittsburgh where leaders agreed that "inefficient fossil fuel subsidies encourage wasteful consumption, reduce our energy security, impede investment in clean sources and undermine efforts to deal with the threat of climate change".
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] If this commitment is followed through and subsidies are removed, a fairer market in which algae biofuels can compete will be created.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] House of Representatives passed a legislation seeking to give algae-based biofuels parity with cellulose biofuels in federal tax credit programs.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] The algae-based renewable fuel promotion act (HR 4168) was implemented to give biofuel projects access to a $1.01 per gal production tax credit and 50% bonus depreciation for biofuel plant property.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] Government also introduced the domestic Fuel for Enhancing National Security Act implemented in 2011.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] This policy constitutes an amendment to the Federal property and administrative services act of 1949 and federal defense provisions in order to extend to 15 the number of years that the Department of Defense (DOD) multiyear contract may be entered into the case of the purchase of advanced biofuel.
[src:alcohol-fuel/algae-fuel] The European Union (EU) has also responded by quadrupling the credits for second-generation algae biofuels which was established as an amendment to the Biofuels and Fuel Quality Directives.
[src:alcohol-fuel/aliphatic] In organic chemistry, hydrocarbons (compounds composed solely of carbon and hydrogen) are divided into two classes: aromatic compounds and **aliphatic compounds** (/ˌælɪˈfætɪk/; G.
[src:alcohol-fuel/aliphatic] Aliphatic compounds can be saturated (in which all the C-C bonds are single, requiring the structure to be completed, or 'saturated', by hydrogen) like hexane, or unsaturated, like hexene and hexyne.
[src:alcohol-fuel/aliphatic] Open-chain compounds, whether straight or branched, and which contain no rings of any type, are always aliphatic.
[src:alcohol-fuel/aliphatic] Cyclic compounds can be aliphatic if they are not aromatic.
[src:alcohol-fuel/aliphatic] Aliphatic compounds can be saturated, joined by single bonds (alkanes), or unsaturated, with double bonds (alkenes) or triple bonds (alkynes).
[src:alcohol-fuel/aliphatic] If other elements (heteroatoms) are bound to the carbon chain, the most common being oxygen, nitrogen, sulfur, and chlorine, it is no longer a hydrocarbon, and therefore no longer an aliphatic compound.
[src:alcohol-fuel/aliphatic] However, such compounds may still be referred to as aliphatic if the hydrocarbon portion of the molecule is aliphatic, e.g. aliphatic amines, to differentiate them from aromatic amines.
[src:alcohol-fuel/aliphatic] The least complex aliphatic compound is methane (CH4).
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] , with global sales of about 134,500 units.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] An **alternative fuel vehicle** is a motor vehicle that runs on alternative fuel rather than traditional petroleum-based fossil fuels such as gasoline, petrodiesel or liquefied petroleum gas (autogas).
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] The term typically refers to internal combustion engine vehicles or fuel cell vehicles that utilize synthetic renewable fuels such as biofuels (ethanol fuel, biodiesel and biogasoline), hydrogen fuel or so-called "Electrofuel".
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] The term can also be used to describe an electric vehicle (particularly a battery electric vehicle or a solar vehicle), which should be more appropriately called an "**alternative energy vehicle**" or "**new energy vehicle**" as its propulsion actually relies on electricity rather than motor fuel.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] Vehicle engines powered by gasoline/petrol first emerged in the 1860s and 1870s; they took until the 1930s to completely dominate the original "alternative" engines driven by steam (18th century), by gases (early 19th century), or by electricity (c.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] Other research and development efforts in alternative forms of power focus on developing plug-in electric, range extender and fuel cell vehicles, and even compressed-air vehicles.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] An environmental analysis of the impacts of various vehicle-fuels extends beyond just operating efficiency and emissions, especially if a technology comes into wide use.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] A life-cycle assessment of a vehicle involves production and post-use considerations.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] In general, the lifecycle greenhouse gas emissions of battery-electric vehicles are lower than emissions from hydrogen, PHEV, hybrid, compressed natural gas, gasoline, and diesel vehicles.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] A flexible-fuel vehicle (FFV) or dual-fuel vehicle (DFF) is an alternative fuel automobile or light duty truck with a multifuel engine that can use more than one fuel, usually mixed in the same tank, and the blend is burned in the combustion chamber together.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] These vehicles are colloquially called **flex-fuel**, or **flexifuel** in Europe, or just flex in Brazil.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] FFVs are distinguished from bi-fuel vehicles, where two fuels are stored in separate tanks.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] The most common commercially available FFV in the world market is the ethanol flexible-fuel vehicle, with the major markets concentrated in the United States, Brazil, Sweden, and some other European countries.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] Ethanol flexible-fuel vehicles have standard gasoline engines that are capable of running with ethanol and gasoline mixed in the same tank.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] These mixtures have "E" numbers which describe the percentage of ethanol in the mixture, for example, E85 is 85% ethanol and 15% gasoline.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] (See common ethanol fuel mixtures for more information.) Though technology exists to allow ethanol FFVs to run on any mixture up to E100, in the U.S. and Europe, flex-fuel vehicles are optimized to run on E85.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] This limit is set to avoid cold starting problems during very cold weather.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] Over 65 million flex fuel automobiles, motorcycles and light duty trucks by the end of 2021, led by Brazil with 38.3 million and the United States with 27 million.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] Other markets were Canada (1.6 million by 2014), and Sweden (243,100 through December 2014).
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] The Brazilian flex fuel fleet includes over 4 million flexible-fuel motorcycles produced since 2009 through March 2015.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] In Brazil, 65% of flex-fuel car owners were using ethanol fuel regularly in 2009, while, the actual number of American FFVs being run on E85 is much lower; surveys conducted in the U.S. have found that 68% of American flex-fuel car owners were not aware they owned an E85 flex.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] Battery electric vehicles (BEVs), also known as all-electric vehicles (AEVs), are electric vehicles whose main energy storage is in the chemical energy of batteries.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] BEVs are the most common form of what is defined by the California Air Resources Board (CARB) as zero emission vehicle (ZEV) because they produce no tailpipe emissions at the point of operation.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] The electrical energy carried on board a BEV to power the motors is obtained from a variety of battery chemistries arranged into battery packs.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] For additional range genset trailers or pusher trailers are sometimes used, forming a type of hybrid vehicle.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] Batteries used in electric vehicles include "flooded" lead-acid, absorbed glass mat, NiCd, nickel metal hydride, Li-ion, Li-poly and zinc-air batteries.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] Attempts at building viable, modern battery-powered electric vehicles began in the 1950s with the introduction of the first modern (transistor controlled) electric car – the Henney Kilowatt, even though the concept was out in the market since 1890.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] Despite the poor sales of the early battery-powered vehicles, development of various battery-powered vehicles continued through the mid-1990s, with such models as the General Motors EV1 and the Toyota RAV4 EV.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] Battery powered cars had primarily used lead-acid batteries and NiMH batteries.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] Lead-acid batteries' recharge capacity is considerably reduced if they're discharged beyond 75% on a regular basis, making them a less-than-ideal solution.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] NiMH batteries are a better choice, but are considerably more expensive than lead-acid.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] Lithium-ion battery powered vehicles such as the Venturi Fetish and the Tesla Roadster have recently demonstrated excellent performance and range, and nevertheless is used in most mass production models launched since December 2010.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] Expanding on traditional lithium-ion batteries predominately used in today's battery electric vehicles, is an emerging science that is paving the way to utilize a carbon fiber structure (a vehicle body or chassis in this case) as a structural battery.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] Experiments being conducted at the Chalmers University of Technology in Sweden are showing that when coupled with Lithium-ion insertion mechanisms, an enhanced carbon fiber structure can have electromechanical properties.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] This means that the carbon fiber structure itself can act as its own battery/power source for propulsion.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] This would negate the need for traditional heavy battery banks, reducing weight and therefore increasing fuel efficiency.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] The world's all-time top selling highway legal electric car is the Nissan Leaf, released in December 2010, with global sales of more than 250,000 units through December 2016.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] The Tesla Model S, released in June 2012, ranks second with global sales of over 158,000 cars delivered as of December 2016.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] The Renault Kangoo Z.E. utility van is the leader of the light-duty all-electric segment with global sales of 25,205 units through December 2016.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] Plug-in hybrid electric vehicles (PHEVs) use batteries to power an electric motor, as well as another fuel, such as gasoline or diesel, to power an internal combustion engine or other propulsion source.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] PHEVs can charge their batteries through charging equipment and regenerative braking.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] Using electricity from the grid to run the vehicle some or all of the time reduces operating costs and fuel use, relative to conventional vehicles.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] Until 2010 most plug-in hybrids on the road in the U.S. were conversions of conventional hybrid electric vehicles, and the most prominent PHEVs were conversions of 2004 or later Toyota Prius, which have had plug-in charging and more batteries added and their electric-only range extended.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] Chinese battery manufacturer and automaker BYD Auto released the F3DM to the Chinese fleet market in December 2008 and began sales to the general public in Shenzhen in March 2010.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] General Motors began deliveries of the Chevrolet Volt in the U.S. in December 2010.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] Deliveries to retail customers of the Fisker Karma began in the U.S. in November 2011.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] During 2012, the Toyota Prius Plug-in Hybrid, Ford C-Max Energi, and Volvo V60 Plug-in Hybrid were released.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] As of December 2015, about 500,000 highway-capable plug-in hybrid electric cars had been sold worldwide since December 2008, out of total cumulative global sales of 1.2 million light-duty plug-in electric vehicles.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] As of December 2016, the Volt/Ampera family of plug-in hybrids, with combined sales of about 134,500 units is the top selling plug-in hybrid in the world.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] Ranking next are the Mitsubishi Outlander P-HEV with about 119,500, and the Toyota Prius Plug-in Hybrid with almost 78,000.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] The first commercial vehicle that used ethanol as a fuel was the Ford Model T, produced from 1908 through 1927.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] It was fitted with a carburetor with adjustable jetting, allowing use of gasoline or ethanol, or a combination of both.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] Other car manufactures also provided engines for ethanol fuel use.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] In the United States, alcohol fuel was produced in corn-alcohol stills until Prohibition criminalized the production of alcohol in 1919.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] The use of alcohol as a fuel for internal combustion engines, either alone or in combination with other fuels, lapsed until the oil price shocks of the 1970s.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] Furthermore, additional attention was gained because of its possible environmental and long-term economical advantages over fossil fuel.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] Both ethanol and methanol have been used as an automotive fuel.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] While both can be obtained from petroleum or natural gas, ethanol has attracted more attention because it is considered a renewable resource, easily obtained from sugar or starch in crops and other agricultural produce such as grain, sugarcane, sugar beets or even lactose.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] Since ethanol occurs in nature whenever yeast happens to find a sugar solution such as overripe fruit, most organisms have evolved some tolerance to ethanol, whereas methanol is toxic.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] Other experiments involve butanol, which can also be produced by fermentation of plants.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] Support for ethanol comes from the fact that it is a biomass fuel, which addresses climate change and greenhouse gas emissions, though these benefits are now highly debated, including the heated 2008 food vs fuel debate.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] Most modern cars are designed to run on gasoline are capable of running with a blend from 10% up to 15% ethanol mixed into gasoline (E10-E15).
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] With a small amount of redesign, gasoline-powered vehicles can run on ethanol concentrations as high as 85% (E85), the maximum set in the United States and Europe due to cold weather during the winter, or up to 100% (E100) in Brazil, with a warmer climate.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] For this reason, for pure or high ethanol blends to be attractive for users, its price must be lower than gasoline to offset the lower fuel economy.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] In the US, and based on EPA tests for all 2006 E85 models, the average fuel economy for E85 vehicles was found 25.56% lower than unleaded gasoline.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] The EPA-rated mileage of current American flex-fuel vehicles could be considered when making price comparisons, though E85 has octane rating of about 104 and could be used as a substitute for premium gasoline.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] Regional retail E85 prices vary widely across the US, with more favorable prices in the Midwest region, where most corn is grown and ethanol produced.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] In August 2008 the US average spread between the price of E85 and gasoline was 16.9%, while in Indiana was 35%, 30% in Minnesota and Wisconsin, 19% in Maryland, 12 to 15% in California, and just 3% in Utah.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] Depending on the vehicle capabilities, the break even price of E85 usually has to be between 25 and 30% lower than gasoline.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] Reacting to the high price of oil and its growing dependence on imports, in 1975 Brazil launched the Pro-alcool program, a huge government-subsidized effort to manufacture ethanol fuel (from its sugar cane crop) and ethanol-powered automobiles.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] These ethanol-only vehicles were very popular in the 1980s, but became economically impractical when oil prices fell – and sugar prices rose – late in that decade.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] In May 2003 Volkswagen built for the first time a commercial ethanol flexible fuel car, the Gol 1.6 Total Flex.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] These vehicles were a commercial success and by early 2009 nine other Brazilian manufacturers are producing flexible fuel vehicles: Chevrolet, Fiat, Ford, Peugeot, Renault, Honda, Mitsubishi, Toyota, Citroën, and Nissan.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] The adoption of the flex technology was so rapid, that flexible fuel cars reached 87.6% of new car sales in July 2008.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] As of August 2008, the fleet of "flex" automobiles and light commercial vehicles had reached 6 million new vehicles sold, representing almost 19% of all registered light vehicles.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] The rapid success of "flex" vehicles, as they are popularly known, was made possible by the existence of 33,000 filling stations with at least one ethanol pump available by 2006, a heritage of the *Pro-alcool* program.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] In the United States, initial support to develop alternative fuels by the government was also a response to the 1973 oil crisis, and later on, as a goal to improve air quality.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] California led the search of sustainable alternatives with interest in methanol.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] In 1996, a new FFV Ford Taurus was developed, with models fully capable of running either methanol or ethanol blended with gasoline.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] This ethanol version of the Taurus was the first commercial production of an E85 FFV.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] The momentum of the FFV production programs at the American car companies continued, although by the end of the 1990s, the emphasis was on the FFV E85 version, as it is today.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] Ethanol was preferred over methanol because there is a large support in the farming community and thanks to government's incentive programs and corn-based ethanol subsidies.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] Sweden also tested both the M85 and the E85 flexifuel vehicles, but due to agriculture policy, in the end emphasis was given to the ethanol flexifuel vehicles.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] The main benefit of diesel combustion engines is that they have a 44% fuel burn efficiency; compared with just 25–30% in the best gasoline engines.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] In addition diesel fuel has slightly higher energy density by volume than gasoline.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] This makes diesel engines capable of achieving much better fuel economy than gasoline vehicles.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] Biodiesel (fatty acid methyl ester), is commercially available in most oilseed-producing states in the United States.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] As of 2005, it is somewhat more expensive than fossil diesel, though it is still commonly produced in relatively small quantities (in comparison to petroleum products and ethanol).
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] Many farmers who raise oilseeds use a biodiesel blend in tractors and equipment as a matter of policy, to foster production of biodiesel and raise public awareness.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] It is sometimes easier to find biodiesel in rural areas than in cities.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] Biodiesel has lower energy density than fossil diesel fuel, so biodiesel vehicles are not quite able to keep up with the fuel economy of a fossil fuelled diesel vehicle, if the diesel injection system is not reset for the new fuel.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] If the injection timing is changed to take account of the higher cetane value of biodiesel, the difference in economy is negligible.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] Because biodiesel contains more oxygen than diesel or vegetable oil fuel, it produces the lowest emissions from diesel engines, and is lower in most emissions than gasoline engines.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] Biodiesel has a higher lubricity than mineral diesel and is an additive in European pump diesel for lubricity and emissions reduction.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] Some diesel-powered cars can run with minor modifications on 100% pure vegetable oils.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] Vegetable oils tend to thicken (or solidify if it is waste cooking oil), in cold weather conditions so vehicle modifications (a two tank system with diesel start/stop tank), are essential in order to heat the fuel prior to use under most circumstances.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] Heating to the temperature of engine coolant reduces fuel viscosity, to the range cited by injection system manufacturers, for systems prior to 'common rail' or 'unit injection ( VW PD)' systems.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] Waste vegetable oil, especially if it has been used for a long time, may become hydrogenated and have increased acidity.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] This can cause the thickening of fuel, gumming in the engine and acid damage of the fuel system.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] Biodiesel does not have this problem, because it is chemically processed to be PH neutral and lower viscosity.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] Vegetable oil fuel is not suitable for these vehicles as they are currently produced.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] This reduces the market as increasing numbers of new vehicles are not able to use it.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] However, the German Elsbett company has successfully produced single tank vegetable oil fuel systems for several decades, and has worked with Volkswagen on their TDI engines.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] This shows that it is technologically possible to use vegetable oil as a fuel in high efficiency / low emission diesel engines.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] Greasestock is an event held yearly in Yorktown Heights, New York, and is one of the largest showcases of vehicles using waste oil as a biofuel in the United States.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] Compressed biogas may be used for internal combustion engines after purification of the raw gas.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] The removal of H2O, H2S and particles can be seen as standard producing a gas which has the same quality as compressed natural gas.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] High-pressure compressed natural gas (CNG), mainly composed of methane, that is used to fuel normal combustion engines instead of gasoline.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] Combustion of methane produces the least amount of CO2 of all fossil fuels.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] Gasoline cars can be retrofitted to CNG and become bifuel Natural gas vehicles (NGVs) as the gasoline tank is kept.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] The driver can switch between CNG and gasoline during operation.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] Natural gas vehicles (NGVs) are popular in regions or countries where natural gas is abundant.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] Widespread use began in the Po River Valley of Italy, and later became very popular in New Zealand by the eighties, though its use has declined.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] As of 2017, there were 24.5 million natural gas vehicles worldwide, led by China (5.35 million) followed by Iran (4.0 million), India (3.05 million), Pakistan (3 million), Argentina (2.3 million), and Brazil (1.78 million).
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] As of 2010, the Asia-Pacific region led the global market with a share of 54%.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] In Europe they are popular in Italy (730,000), Ukraine (200,000), Armenia (101,352), Russia (100,000) and Germany (91,500), and they are becoming more so as various manufacturers produce factory made cars, buses, vans and heavy vehicles.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] In the United States CNG powered buses are the favorite choice of several public transit agencies, with an estimated CNG bus fleet of some 130,000.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] Other countries where CNG-powered buses are popular include India, Australia, Argentina, and Germany.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] CNG vehicles are common in South America, where these vehicles are mainly used as taxicabs in main cities of Argentina and Brazil.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] Normally, standard gasoline vehicles are retrofitted in specialized shops, which involve installing the gas cylinder in the trunk and the CNG injection system and electronics.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] The Brazilian GNV fleet is concentrated in the cities of Rio de Janeiro and São Paulo.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] Pike Research reports that almost 90% of NGVs in Latin America have bi-fuel engines, allowing these vehicles to run on either gasoline or CNG.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] Dual fuel vehicle is referred as the vehicle using two types of fuel in the same time (can be gas + liquid, gas + gas, liquid + liquid) with different fuel tank.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] Diesel-CNG dual fuel is a system using two type of fuel which are diesel and compressed natural gas (CNG) at the same time.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] It is because of CNG need a source of ignition for combustion in diesel engine.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] A hybrid vehicle uses multiple propulsion systems to provide motive power.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] The most common type of hybrid vehicle is the gasoline-electric hybrid vehicles, which use gasoline (petrol) and electric batteries for the energy used to power internal-combustion engines (ICEs) and electric motors.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] These motors are usually relatively small and would be considered "underpowered" by themselves, but they can provide a normal driving experience when used in combination during acceleration and other maneuvers that require greater power.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] The Toyota Prius first went on sale in Japan in 1997 and it is sold worldwide since 2000.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] As of January 2017, there are over 50 models of hybrid electric cars available in several world markets, with more than 12 million hybrid electric vehicles sold worldwide since their inception in 1997.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] A hydrogen car is an automobile which uses hydrogen as its primary source of power for locomotion.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] These cars generally use the hydrogen in one of two methods: combustion or fuel-cell conversion.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] In combustion, the hydrogen is "burned" in engines in fundamentally the same method as traditional gasoline cars.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] The common internal combustion engine, usually fueled with gasoline (petrol) or diesel liquids, can be converted to run on gaseous hydrogen.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] This emits water at the point of use, and during combustion with air NOx can be produced.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] However, the most efficient use of hydrogen involves the use of fuel cells and electric motors instead of a traditional engine.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] Hydrogen reacts with oxygen inside the fuel cells, which produces electricity to power the motors, with the only byproduct from the spent hydrogen being water.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] A small number of commercially available hydrogen fuel cell cars currently exist: the Hyundai NEXO, Toytota Mirai, and previously the Honda FCX Clarity.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] One primary area of research is hydrogen storage, to try to increase the range of hydrogen vehicles while reducing the weight, energy consumption, and complexity of the storage systems.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] Two primary methods of storage are metal hydrides and compression.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] Some believe that hydrogen cars will never be economically viable and that the emphasis on this technology is a diversion from the development and popularization of more efficient battery electric vehicles.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] In the light road vehicle segment, by the end of 2022, 70,200 hydrogen fuel cell electric vehicles had been sold worldwide, compared with 26 million plug-in electric vehicles.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] With the rapid rise of electric vehicles and associated battery technology and infrastructure, the global scope for hydrogen's role in cars is shrinking relative to earlier expectations.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] Electric power fed from an external source to the vehicle is standard in railway electrification.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] At such systems usually the tracks form one pole, while the other is usually a single overhead wire or a rail insulated against ground.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] On roads this system does not work as described, as normal road surfaces are very poor electric conductors; and so electric vehicles fed with external power on roads require at least two overhead wires.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] The most common type of road vehicles fed with electricity from external source are trolleybusses, but there are also some trucks powered with this technology.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] The advantage is that the vehicle can be operated without breaks for refueling or charging.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] Disadvantages include: a large infrastructure of electric wires; difficulty in driving as one has to prevent a dewirement of the vehicle; vehicles cannot overtake each other; a danger of electrocution; and an aesthetic problem.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] Wireless transmission (see Wireless power transfer) is possible, in principle; but the infrastructure (especially wiring) necessary for inductive or capacitive coupling would be extensive and expensive.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] In principle it is also possible to transmit energy by microwaves or by lasers to the vehicle, but this may be inefficient and dangerous for the power required.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] Beside this, in the case of lasers one requires a guidance system to track the vehicle to be powered, as laser beams have a small diameter.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] Comparative assessments of conventional fossil and alternative fuel vehicles usually encompass more than in-use environmental impacts and running costs.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] They factor in issues like resource extractive impacts (e.g. for battery manufacture or fossil fuel extraction), 'well-to-wheel' efficiency, and the carbon intensity of electricity in different geographies.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p01] BEVs have lower emissions than internal combustion engine vehicles even in places where electricity generation is relatively carbon-intensive, for example China where electricity is predominantly generated from coal.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] The air engine is an emission-free piston engine that uses compressed air as a source of energy.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] The first compressed air car was invented by a French engineer named Guy Nègre.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] The expansion of compressed air may be used to drive the pistons in a modified piston engine.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] Efficiency of operation is gained through the use of environmental heat at normal temperature to warm the otherwise cold expanded air from the storage tank.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] This non-adiabatic expansion has the potential to greatly increase the efficiency of the machine.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] The only exhaust is cold air (−15 °C), which could also be used to air condition the car.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] The source for air is a pressurized carbon-fiber tank.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] Air is delivered to the engine via a rather conventional injection system.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] Unique crank design within the engine increases the time during which the air charge is warmed from ambient sources and a two-stage process allows improved heat transfer rates.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] Electricity can be also stored in supercapacitors and superconductors.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] However superconductor storage is unsuitable for vehicle propulsion as it requires extremely low temperatures and produces strong magnetic fields.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] Supercapacitors, however, can be used in vehicles and are used in some trams on sections without overhead wire.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] They can be charged during regular stops, while passengers enter and leave the train, but can only travel a few kilometres with the stored energy.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] However, this is no problem in this case as the next stop is usually in reachable distance.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] A solar car is an electric vehicle powered by solar energy obtained from solar panels on the car.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] Solar panels cannot currently be used to directly supply a car with a suitable amount of power at this time, but they can be used to extend the range of electric vehicles.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] As of 2022, a handful of solar electric cars with varying performance are becoming commercially available, from Fisker and Lightyear, among others.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] Solar cars are raced in competitions such as the World Solar Challenge and the North American Solar Challenge.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] These events are often sponsored by Government agencies such as the United States Department of Energy keen to promote the development of alternative energy technology such as solar cells and electric vehicles.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] Such challenges are often entered by universities to develop their students' engineering and technological skills as well as motor vehicle manufacturers such as GM and Honda.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] Dimethyl ether (DME) is a promising fuel in diesel engines, petrol engines (30% DME / 70% LPG), and gas turbines owing to its high cetane number, which is 55, compared to diesel's, which is 40–53.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] Only moderate modifications are needed to convert a diesel engine to burn DME.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] The simplicity of this short carbon chain compound leads during combustion to very low emissions of particulate matter, NOx, CO.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] For these reasons as well as being sulfur-free, DME meets even the most stringent emission regulations in Europe (EURO5), U.S.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] Mobil is using DME in their methanol to gasoline process.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] DME is being developed as a synthetic second generation biofuel (BioDME), which can be manufactured from lignocellulosic biomass.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] In 2006 the EU considered BioDME in its potential biofuel mix in 2030; the Volvo Group was the coordinator for the European Community Seventh Framework Programme project BioDME where Chemrec's BioDME pilot plant based on black liquor gasification is nearing completion in Piteå, Sweden.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] Ammonia is produced by combining gaseous hydrogen with nitrogen from the air.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] Large-scale ammonia production uses natural gas for the source of hydrogen.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] Ammonia was used during World War II to power buses in Belgium, and in engine and solar energy applications prior to 1900.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] Liquid ammonia also fuelled the Reaction Motors XLR99 rocket engine, that powered the X-15 hypersonic research aircraft.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] Although not as powerful as other fuels, it left no soot in the reusable rocket engine and its density approximately matches the density of the oxidizer, liquid oxygen, which simplified the aircraft's design.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] Ammonia has been proposed as a practical alternative to fossil fuel for internal combustion engines.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] The calorific value of ammonia is 22.5 MJ/kg (9690 BTU/lb), which is about half that of diesel.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] In a normal engine, in which the water vapour is not condensed, the calorific value of ammonia will be about 21% less than this figure.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] It can be used in existing engines with only minor modifications to carburettors/injectors.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] When ammonia is produced using coal, the CO2 emitted has the potential to be sequestered (the combustion products are nitrogen and water).
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] Ammonia engines or ammonia motors, using ammonia as a working fluid, have been proposed and occasionally used.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] The principle is similar to that used in a fireless locomotive, but with ammonia as the working fluid, instead of steam or compressed air.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] Ammonia engines were used experimentally in the 19th century by Goldsworthy Gurney in the UK and in streetcars in New Orleans.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] In 1981 a Canadian company converted a 1981 Chevrolet Impala to operate using ammonia as fuel.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] Ammonia and GreenNH3 is being used with success by developers in Canada, since it can run in spark ignited or diesel engines with minor modifications, also the only green fuel to power jet engines, and despite its toxicity is reckoned to be no more dangerous than petrol or LPG.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] It can be made from renewable electricity, and having half the density of petrol or diesel can be readily carried in sufficient quantities in vehicles.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] On complete combustion it has no emissions other than nitrogen and water vapour.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] The combustion chemical formula is 4 NH3 + 3 O2 → 2 N2 + 6 H2O, 75% water is the result.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] In the 1930s Tang Zhongming made an invention using abundant charcoal resources for Chinese auto market.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] The charcoal-fuelled car was later used intensively in China, serving the army and conveyancer after the outbreak of World War II.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] Liquefied natural gas (LNG) is natural gas that has been cooled to a point at which it becomes a cryogenic liquid.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] In this liquid state, natural gas is more than 2 times as dense as highly compressed CNG.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] LNG fuel systems function on any vehicle capable of burning natural gas.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] Unlike CNG, which is stored at high pressure (typically 3000 or 3600 psi) and then regulated to a lower pressure that the engine can accept, LNG is stored at low pressure (50 to 150 psi) and simply vaporized by a heat exchanger before entering the fuel metering devices to the engine.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] Because of its high energy density compared to CNG, it is very suitable for those interested in long ranges while running on natural gas.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] In the United States, the LNG supply chain is the main thing that has held back this fuel source from growing rapidly.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] The LNG supply chain is very analogous to that of diesel or gasoline.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] First, pipeline natural gas is liquefied in large quantities, which is analogous to refining gasoline or diesel.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] Then, the LNG is transported via semi trailer to fuel stations where it is stored in bulk tanks until it is dispensed into a vehicle.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] CNG, on the other hand, requires expensive compression at each station to fill the high-pressure cylinder cascades.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] LPG or liquefied petroleum gas (LPG) is a low pressure liquefied gas mixture composed mainly of propane and butane which burns in conventional gasoline combustion engines with less CO2 than gasoline.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] Gasoline cars can be retrofitted to LPG aka Autogas and become bifuel vehicles as the gasoline tank is not removed, allowing drivers to switch between LPG and gasoline during operation.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] Estimated 10 million vehicles running worldwide.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] There are 24.9 million LPG powered vehicles worldwide as of December 2013, led by Turkey with 3.93 million, South Korea (2.4 million), and Poland (2.75 million).
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] In the U.S., 190,000 on-road vehicles use propane, and 450,000 forklifts use it for power.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] However, it is banned in Pakistan (DEC 2013) as it is considered a risk to public safety by OGRA.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] Formic acid is used by converting it first to hydrogen, and using that in a hydrogen fuel cell.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] It can also be used directly in formic acid fuel cells.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] Formic acid is much easier to store than hydrogen.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] Liquid nitrogen (LN2) is a method of storing energy.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] Energy is used to liquefy air, and then LN2 is produced by evaporation, and distributed.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] LN2 is exposed to ambient heat in the car and the resulting nitrogen gas can be used to power a piston or turbine engine.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] The maximum amount of energy that can be extracted from LN2 is 213 Watt-hours per kg (W·h/kg) or 173 W·h per liter, in which a maximum of 70 W·h/kg can be utilized with an isothermal expansion process.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] Such a vehicle with a 350-liter (93 gallon) tank can achieve ranges similar to a gasoline powered vehicle with a 50-liter (13 gallon) tank.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] Theoretical future engines, using cascading topping cycles, can improve this to around 110 W·h/kg with a quasi-isothermal expansion process.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] The advantages are zero harmful emissions and superior energy densities compared to a compressed-air vehicle as well as being able to refill the tank in a matter of minutes.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] In principle, it is possible to build a vehicle powered by nuclear fission or nuclear decay.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] However, there are two major problems: first one has to transform the energy, which comes as heat and radiation into energy usable for a drive.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] One possible would be to use a steam turbine as in a nuclear power plant, but such a device would take too much space.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] A more suitable way would be direct conversion into electricity for example with thermoelements or thermionic devices.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] The second problem is that nuclear fission produces high levels of neutron and gamma rays, which require excessive shielding, that would result in a vehicle too large for use on public roads.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] However studies were made in this way by Ford Nucleon.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] A better way for a nuclear powered vehicle would be the use of power of radioactive decay in radioisotope thermoelectric generators, which are also very safe and reliable.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] The required shielding of these devices depends on the used radio nuclide.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] Plutonium-238 as nearly pure alpha radiator does not require much shielding.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] As prices for suitable radionuclide are high and energy density is low (generating 1 watt with plutonium-238 requires a half gram of it), this way of propulsion is too expensive for wide use.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] Also radioisotope thermoelectric generators offer according to their large content of high radioactive material an extreme danger in case of misuse for example by terrorists.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] The only vehicle in use, which is driven by radioisotope thermoelectric generators is the Mars rover Curiosity.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] Other forms of nuclear power as fusion and annihilation are at present not available for vehicle propulsion, as no working fusion reactor is available and it is questionable if one can ever built one with a size suitable for a road vehicle.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] Annihilation may perhaps work in some ways (see antimatter drive), but there is no technology existing to produce and store enough antimatter.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] In very small vehicles, the power demand decreases, so human power can be employed to make a significant improvement in battery life.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] Three such commercially made vehicles are the Sinclair C5, ELF and TWIKE.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] Flywheels can be also used for alternative fuel and were used in the 1950s for the propulsion of buses in Switzerland, the such called gyrobuses.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] The flywheel of the bus was loaded up by electric power at the terminals of the line and allowed it to travel a way up to 8 kilometres just with its flywheel.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] Flywheel-powered vehicles are quieter than vehicles with combustion engine, require no overhead wire and generate no exhausts, but the flywheel device has a great weight (1.5 tons for 5 kWh) and requires special safety measures due to its high rotational speed.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] Silanes higher than heptasilane can be stored like gasoline and may also work as fuel.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] They have the advantage that they can also burn with the nitrogen of the air, but have as major disadvantage its high price and that its combustion products are solid, which gives trouble in combustion engines.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] The power of wound-up springs or twisted rubber cords can be used for the propulsion of small vehicles.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] However this way of energy storage allows only saving small energy amounts not suitable for the propulsion of vehicles for transporting people.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] Spring-powered vehicles are wind-up toys or mousetrap cars.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] A steam car is a car that has a steam engine.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] Wood, coal, ethanol, or others can be used as fuel.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] The fuel is burned in a boiler and the heat converts water into steam.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] When the water turns to steam, it expands.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] The pressure pushes the pistons back and forth.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] This turns the driveshaft to spin the wheels which provides moves the car forward.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] It works like a coal-fueled steam train, or steam boat.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] The steam car was the next logical step in independent transport.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] Steam cars take a long time to start, but some can reach speeds over 100 mph (161 km/h) eventually.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] The late model Doble steam cars could be brought to operational condition in less than 30 seconds, had high top speeds and fast acceleration, but were expensive to buy.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] A steam engine uses external combustion, as opposed to internal combustion.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] Gasoline-powered cars are more efficient at about 25–28% efficiency.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] In theory, a combined cycle steam engine in which the burning material is first used to drive a gas turbine can produce 50% to 60% efficiency.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] However, practical examples of steam engined cars work at only around 5–8% efficiency.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] The best known and best selling steam-powered car was the Stanley Steamer.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] It used a compact fire-tube boiler under the hood to power a simple two-piston engine which was connected directly to the rear axle.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] Before Henry Ford introduced monthly payment financing with great success, cars were typically purchased outright.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] This is why the Stanley was kept simple; to keep the purchase price affordable.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] Steam produced in refrigeration also can be use by a turbine in other vehicle types to produce electricity, that can be employed in electric motors or stored in a battery.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] Steam power can be combined with a standard oil-based engine to create a hybrid.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] Water is injected into the cylinder after the fuel is burned, when the piston is still superheated, often at temperatures of 1500 degrees or more.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] The water will instantly be vaporized into steam, taking advantage of the heat that would otherwise be wasted.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] Wind-powered vehicles have been well known for a long time.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] They can be realized with sails similar to those used on ships, by using an onboard wind turbine, which drives the wheels directly or which generates electricity for an electric motor, or can be pulled by a kite.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] Wind-powered land vehicles need an enormous clearance in height, especially when sails or kites are used and are unsuitable in urban area.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] Wind-powered vehicles are only used for recreational activities on beaches or other free areas.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] The concept is described in further detail here: de:Segelwagen.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] Wood gas can be used to power cars with ordinary internal combustion engines if a wood gasifier is attached.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] This was quite popular during World War II in several European and Asian countries because the war prevented easy and cost-effective access to oil.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] As of 2014, Herb Hartman of Woodward, Iowa currently drives a wood powered Cadillac.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] He claims to have attached the gasifier to the Cadillac for just $700.
[src:alcohol-fuel/alternative-fuel-vehicle-p02] Hartman claims, "A full hopper will go about fifty miles depending on how you drive it," and he added that splitting the wood was "labor-intensive.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Anaerobic digestion reduces sludge volume and pathogen content while generating methane-rich biogas that can be used for renewable energy production.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] The liquid remainder, digestate can be further treated and, in some cases, beneficially reused.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Anaerobic digestion occurs naturally in some soils and in lake and oceanic basin sediments, where it is usually referred to as "anaerobic activity".
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] This is the source of marsh gas methane as discovered by Alessandro Volta in 1776.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] The digestion process begins with bacterial hydrolysis of the input materials.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Insoluble organic polymers, such as carbohydrates, are broken down to soluble derivatives that become available for other bacteria.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Acidogenic bacteria then convert the sugars and amino acids into carbon dioxide, hydrogen, ammonia, and organic acids.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] In acetogenesis, bacteria convert these resulting organic acids into acetic acid, along with additional ammonia, hydrogen, and carbon dioxide amongst other compounds.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Finally, methanogens convert these products to methane and carbon dioxide.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] The methanogenic archaea populations play an indispensable role in anaerobic wastewater treatments.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Anaerobic digestion is used as part of the process to treat biodegradable waste and sewage sludge.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] As part of an integrated waste management system, anaerobic digestion reduces the emission of landfill gas into the atmosphere.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Anaerobic digesters can also be fed with purpose-grown energy crops, such as maize.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Anaerobic digestion is widely used as a source of renewable energy.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] The process produces a biogas, consisting of methane, carbon dioxide, and traces of other 'contaminant' gases.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] This biogas can be used directly as fuel, in combined heat and power gas engines or upgraded to natural gas-quality biomethane.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] The nutrient-rich digestate also produced can be used as fertilizer.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Many microorganisms affect anaerobic digestion, including acetic acid-forming bacteria (acetogens) and methane-forming archaea (methanogens).
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] These organisms promote a number of chemical processes in converting the biomass to biogas.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Gaseous oxygen is excluded from the reactions by physical containment.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Anaerobes utilize electron acceptors from sources other than oxygen gas.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] These acceptors can be the organic material itself or may be supplied by inorganic oxides from within the input material.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] When the oxygen source in an anaerobic system is derived from the organic material itself, the 'intermediate' end products are primarily alcohols, aldehydes, and organic acids, plus carbon dioxide.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] In the presence of specialised methanogens, the intermediates are converted to the 'final' end products of methane, carbon dioxide, and trace levels of hydrogen sulfide.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] In an anaerobic system, the majority of the chemical energy contained within the starting material is released by methanogenic archaea as methane.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Populations of anaerobic microorganisms typically take a significant period of time to establish themselves to be fully effective.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Therefore, common practice is to introduce anaerobic microorganisms from materials with existing populations, a process known as "seeding" the digesters, typically accomplished with the addition of sewage sludge or cattle slurry.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] The four key stages of anaerobic digestion involve hydrolysis, acidogenesis, acetogenesis and methanogenesis.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] The overall process can be described by the chemical reaction, where organic material such as glucose is biochemically digested into carbon dioxide (CO2) and methane (CH4) by the anaerobic microorganisms.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] In most cases, biomass is made up of large organic polymers.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] For the bacteria in anaerobic digesters to access the energy potential of the material, these chains must first be broken down into their smaller constituent parts.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] These constituent parts, or monomers, such as sugars, are readily available to other bacteria.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] The process of breaking these chains and dissolving the smaller molecules into solution is called hydrolysis.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Therefore, hydrolysis of these high-molecular-weight polymeric components is the necessary first step in anaerobic digestion.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Acetate and hydrogen produced in the first stages can be used directly by methanogens.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] into compounds that can be directly used by methanogens.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] results in further breakdown of the remaining components by acidogenic (fermentative) bacteria.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Here, simple molecules created through the acidogenesis phase are further digested by acetogens to produce largely acetic acid, as well as carbon dioxide and hydrogen.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Here, methanogens use the intermediate products of the preceding stages and convert them into methane, carbon dioxide, and water.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] These components make up the majority of the biogas emitted from the system.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Methanogenesis is sensitive to both high and low pHs and occurs between pH 6.5 and pH 8.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] The remaining, indigestible material the microbes cannot use and any dead bacterial remains constitute the digestate.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Process performance depends on several operational parameters, including temperature (mesophilic conditions at approximately 35–37 °C or thermophilic conditions at 50–55 °C), organic loading rate (OLR), pH (typically maintained between 6.8 and 7.2), and solids retention time (SRT).
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Proper control of these parameters is essential to prevent process instability and volatile fatty acid accumulation.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Anaerobic digesters can be designed and engineered to operate using a number of different configurations and can be categorized into batch vs. continuous process mode, mesophilic vs. thermophilic temperature conditions, high vs. low portion of solids, and single stage vs. multistage processes.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Higher heat energy is required in a thermophilic system compared to a mesophilic system, but the thermophilic system requires much less time and has a larger gas output capacity and higher methane gas content, so one has to consider that trade-off carefully.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] For solids content, low will handle up to 15% solid content.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Above this level is considered high solids content and can also be known as dry digestion.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] In a single stage process, one reactor houses the four anaerobic digestion steps.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] A multistage process utilizes two or more reactors for digestion to separate the methanogenesis and hydrolysis phases.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Anaerobic digestion can be performed as a batch process or a continuous process.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] In a batch system, biomass is added to the reactor at the start of the process.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] The reactor is then sealed for the duration of the process.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] In its simplest form batch processing needs inoculation with already processed material to start the anaerobic digestion.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] In a typical scenario, biogas production will be formed with a normal distribution pattern over time.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Operators can use this fact to determine when they believe the process of digestion of the organic matter has completed.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] There can be severe odour issues if a batch reactor is opened and emptied before the process is well completed.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] A more advanced type of batch approach has limited the odour issues by integrating anaerobic digestion with in-vessel composting.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] In this approach inoculation takes place through the use of recirculated degasified percolate.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] After anaerobic digestion has completed, the biomass is kept in the reactor which is then used for in-vessel composting before it is opened As the batch digestion is simple and requires less equipment and lower levels of design work, it is typically a cheaper form of digestion.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Using more than one batch reactor at a plant can ensure constant production of biogas.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] In continuous digestion processes, organic matter is constantly added (continuous complete mixed) or added in stages to the reactor (continuous plug flow; first in – first out).
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Here, the end products are constantly or periodically removed, resulting in constant production of biogas.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] A single or multiple digesters in sequence may be used.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Examples of this form of anaerobic digestion include continuous stirred-tank reactors, upflow anaerobic sludge blankets, expanded granular sludge beds, and internal circulation reactors.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] A limit case has been reached in Bolivia, with anaerobic digestion in temperature working conditions of less than 10 °C.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] The anaerobic process is very slow, taking more than three times the normal mesophilic time process.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] In experimental work at University of Alaska Fairbanks, a 1,000-litre digester using psychrophiles harvested from "mud from a frozen lake in Alaska" has produced 200–300 litres of methane per day, about 20 to 30% of the output from digesters in warmer climates.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Mesophilic species outnumber thermophiles, and they are also more tolerant to changes in environmental conditions than thermophiles.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Mesophilic systems are, therefore, considered to be more stable than thermophilic digestion systems.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] In contrast, while thermophilic digestion systems are considered less stable, their energy input is higher, with more biogas being removed from the organic matter in an equal amount of time.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] The increased temperatures facilitate faster reaction rates, and thus faster gas yields.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Operation at higher temperatures facilitates greater pathogen reduction of the digestate.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] In countries where legislation, such as the Animal By-Products Regulations in the European Union, requires digestate to meet certain levels of pathogen reduction there may be a benefit to using thermophilic temperatures instead of mesophilic.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Additional pre-treatment can be used to reduce the necessary retention time to produce biogas.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] For example, certain processes shred the substrates to increase the surface area or use a thermal pretreatment stage (such as pasteurisation) to significantly enhance the biogas output.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] The pasteurisation process can also be used to reduce the pathogenic concentration in the digestate, leaving the anaerobic digester.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Pasteurisation may be achieved by heat treatment combined with maceration of the solids.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] High solids (dry) digesters are designed to process materials with a solids content between 25 and 40%.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Unlike wet digesters that process pumpable slurries, high solids (dry – stackable substrate) digesters are designed to process solid substrates without the addition of water.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] The primary styles of dry digesters are continuous vertical plug flow and batch tunnel horizontal digesters.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Continuous vertical plug flow digesters are upright, cylindrical tanks where feedstock is continuously fed into the top of the digester, and flows downward by gravity during digestion.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] In batch tunnel digesters, the feedstock is deposited in tunnel-like chambers with a gas-tight door.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Neither approach has mixing inside the digester.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] The amount of pretreatment, such as contaminant removal, depends both upon the nature of the waste streams being processed and the desired quality of the digestate.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Size reduction (grinding) is beneficial in continuous vertical systems, as it accelerates digestion, while batch systems avoid grinding and instead require structure (e.g. yard waste) to reduce compaction of the stacked pile.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Continuous vertical dry digesters have a smaller footprint due to the shorter effective retention time and vertical design.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Wet digesters can be designed to operate in either a high-solids content, with a total suspended solids (TSS) concentration greater than ~20%, or a low-solids concentration less than ~15%.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] High solids (wet) digesters process a thick slurry that requires more energy input to move and process the feedstock.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] The thickness of the material may also lead to associated problems with abrasion.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] High solids digesters will typically have a lower land requirement due to the lower volumes associated with the moisture.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] High solids digesters also require correction of conventional performance calculations (e.g. gas production, retention time, kinetics, etc.) originally based on very dilute sewage digestion concepts, since larger fractions of the feedstock mass are potentially convertible to biogas.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Low solids (wet) digesters can transport material through the system using standard pumps that require significantly lower energy input.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Low solids digesters require a larger amount of land than high solids due to the increased volumes associated with the increased liquid-to-feedstock ratio of the digesters.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] There are benefits associated with operation in a liquid environment, as it enables more thorough circulation of materials and contact between the bacteria and their food.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] This enables the bacteria to more readily access the substances on which they are feeding, and increases the rate of gas production.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Digestion systems can be configured with different levels of complexity.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] In a **single-stage digestion system** (one-stage), all of the biological reactions occur within a single, sealed reactor or holding tank.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Using a single stage reduces construction costs, but results in less control of the reactions occurring within the system.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Acidogenic bacteria, through the production of acids, reduce the pH of the tank.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Methanogenic archaea, as outlined earlier, operate in a strictly defined pH range.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Therefore, the biological reactions of the different species in a single-stage reactor can be in direct competition with each other.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Another one-stage reaction system is an anaerobic lagoon.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] These lagoons are pond-like, earthen basins used for the treatment and long-term storage of manures.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Here the anaerobic reactions are contained within the natural anaerobic sludge contained in the pool.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] In a **two-stage digestion system** (multistage), different digestion vessels are optimised to bring maximum control over the bacterial communities living within the digesters.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Acidogenic bacteria produce organic acids and more quickly grow and reproduce than methanogenic archaea.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Methanogenic archaea require stable pH and temperature to optimise their performance.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Under typical circumstances, hydrolysis, acetogenesis, and acidogenesis occur within the first reaction vessel.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] The organic material is then heated to the required operational temperature (either mesophilic or thermophilic) prior to being pumped into a methanogenic reactor.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] The initial hydrolysis or acidogenesis tanks prior to the methanogenic reactor can provide a buffer to the rate at which feedstock is added.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Some European countries require a degree of elevated heat treatment to kill harmful bacteria in the input waste.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] In this instance, there may be a pasteurisation or sterilisation stage prior to digestion or between the two digestion tanks.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Notably, it is not possible to completely isolate the different reaction phases, and often some biogas is produced in the hydrolysis or acidogenesis tanks.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] The residence time in a digester varies with the amount and type of feed material, and with the configuration of the digestion system.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] In a typical two-stage mesophilic digestion, residence time varies between 15 and 40 days, while for a single-stage thermophilic digestion, residence times is normally faster and takes around 14 days.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] The plug-flow nature of some of these systems will mean the full degradation of the material may not have been realised in this timescale.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] In this event, digestate exiting the system will be darker in colour and will typically have more odour.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] In the case of an upflow anaerobic sludge blanket digestion (UASB), hydraulic residence times can be as short as 1 hour to 1 day, and solid retention times can be up to 90 days.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] In this manner, a UASB system is able to separate solids and hydraulic retention times with the use of a sludge blanket.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Continuous digesters have mechanical or hydraulic devices, depending on the level of solids in the material, to mix the contents, enabling the bacteria and the food to be in contact.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] They also allow excess material to be continuously extracted to maintain a reasonably constant volume within the digestion tanks.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] A recent development in anaerobic reactor design is High-pressure anaerobic digestion (HPAD) also referred to an Autogenerative High Pressure Digestion (AHPD).
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] This technique produces a biogas with an elevated methane content.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] The produced carbon dioxide in biogas dissolves more into the water phase under pressure than methane does.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Hence the produced biogas is richer in methane.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Research at the University of Groningen demonstrated that the bacterial community changes in composition under the influence of pressure.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Individual bacteria species have their optimum circumstances in which they grow and replicate the fastest.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Commonly known are pH, temperature, salinity etc. but pressure is also one of them.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Some species have adapted to life in the deep oceans where pressure is much higher than at sea level.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] This makes it possible in similar vein as other process parameters such as Temperature, Retention Time, pH to influence the anaerobic digestion process.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] in Germany, 2007 - the green, inflatable biogas holder is shown on top of the digester.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] The anaerobic digestion process can be inhibited by several compounds, affecting one or more of the bacterial groups responsible for the different organic matter degradation steps.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] The degree of the inhibition depends, among other factors, on the concentration of the inhibitor in the digester.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Potential inhibitors are ammonia, sulfide, light metal ions (Na, K, Mg, Ca, Al), heavy metals, some organics (chlorophenols, halogenated aliphatics, N-substituted aromatics, long chain fatty acids), etc.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Total ammonia nitrogen (TAN) has been shown to inhibit production of methane.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Furthermore, it destabilises the microbial community, impacting the synthesis of acetic acid.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Acetic acid is one of the driving forces in methane production.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] At an excess of 5000 mg/L TAN, pH adjustment is needed to keep the reaction stable.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] A TAN concentration above 1700– 1800 mg/L inhibits methane production and yield decreases at greater TAN concentrations.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] High TAN concentrations cause the reaction to turn acidic and lead to a domino effect of inhibition.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Total ammonia nitrogen is the combination of free ammonia and ionized ammonia.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] TAN is produced through degrading material high in nitrogen, typically proteins and will naturally build in anaerobic digestion.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] This is depending on the organic feed stock fed to the system.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] In typical wastewater treatment practices, TAN reduction is done with via nitrification.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Nitrification is an aerobic process where TAN is consumed by aerobic heterotrophic bacteria.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] These bacteria release nitrate and nitrite which are later converted to nitrogen gas through the denitrification process.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Hydrolysis and acidogenesis can also be impacted by TAN concentration.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] In mesophilic conditions, inhibition for hydrolysis was found to occur at 5500 mg/L TAN, while acidogenesis inhibition occurs at 6500 mg/L TAN.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] The most important initial issue when considering the application of anaerobic digestion systems is the feedstock to the process.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Almost any organic material can be processed with anaerobic digestion however, if biogas production is the aim, the level of putrescibility is the key factor in its successful application.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] The more putrescible (digestible) the material, the higher the gas yields possible from the system.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Feedstocks can include biodegradable waste materials, such as waste paper, grass clippings, leftover food, sewage, and animal waste.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Woody wastes are the exception, because they are largely unaffected by digestion, as most anaerobes are unable to degrade lignin.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Xylophagous anaerobes (lignin consumers) or high temperature pretreatment, such as pyrolysis, can be used to break lignin down.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Anaerobic digesters can also be fed with specially grown energy crops, such as silage, for dedicated biogas production.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] In Germany and continental Europe, these facilities are referred to as "biogas" plants.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] A codigestion or cofermentation plant is typically an agricultural anaerobic digester that accepts two or more input materials for simultaneous digestion.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] The length of time required for anaerobic digestion depends on the chemical complexity of the material.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Material rich in easily digestible sugars breaks down quickly, whereas intact lignocellulosic material rich in cellulose and hemicellulose polymers can take much longer to break down.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Anaerobic microorganisms are generally unable to break down lignin, the recalcitrant aromatic component of biomass.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Anaerobic digesters were originally designed for operation using sewage sludge and manures.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Sewage and manure are not, however, the material with the most potential for anaerobic digestion, as the biodegradable material has already had much of the energy content taken out by the animals that produced it.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Therefore, many digesters operate with codigestion of two or more types of feedstock.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Digesters processing dedicated energy crops can achieve high levels of degradation and biogas production.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] A second consideration related to the feedstock is moisture content.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Drier, stackable substrates, such as food and yard waste, are suitable for digestion in tunnel-like chambers.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Tunnel-style systems typically have near-zero wastewater discharge, as well, so this style of system has advantages where the discharge of digester liquids are a liability.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] The wetter the material, the more suitable it will be to handling with standard pumps instead of energy-intensive concrete pumps and physical means of movement.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Also, the wetter the material, the more volume and area it takes up relative to the levels of gas produced.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] The moisture content of the target feedstock will also affect what type of system is applied to its treatment.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] To use a high-solids anaerobic digester for dilute feedstocks, bulking agents, such as compost, should be applied to increase the solids content of the input material.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Another key consideration is the carbon:nitrogen ratio of the input material.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] This ratio is the balance of food a microbe requires to grow; the optimal C:N ratio is 20–30:1.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Excess N can lead to ammonia inhibition of digestion.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] The level of contamination of the feedstock material is a key consideration when using wet digestion or plug-flow digestion.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] If the feedstock to the digesters has significant levels of physical contaminants, such as plastic, glass, or metals, then processing to remove the contaminants will be required for the material to be used.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] If it is not removed, then the digesters can be blocked and will not function efficiently.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] This contamination issue does not occur with dry digestion or solid-state anaerobic digestion (SSAD) plants, since SSAD handles dry, stackable biomass with a high percentage of solids (40-60%) in gas-tight chambers called fermenter boxes.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] It is with this understanding that mechanical biological treatment plants are designed.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] The higher the level of pretreatment a feedstock requires, the more processing machinery will be required, and, hence, the project will have higher capital costs.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] After sorting or screening to remove any physical contaminants from the feedstock, the material is often shredded, minced, and mechanically or hydraulically pulped to increase the surface area available to microbes in the digesters and, hence, increase the speed of digestion.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] The maceration of solids can be achieved by using a chopper pump to transfer the feedstock material into the airtight digester, where anaerobic treatment takes place.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Substrate composition is a major factor in determining the methane yield and methane production rates from the digestion of biomass.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Techniques to determine the compositional characteristics of the feedstock are available, while parameters such as solids, elemental, and organic analyses are important for digester design and operation.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Methane yield can be estimated from the elemental composition of substrate along with an estimate of its degradability (the fraction of the substrate that is converted to biogas in a reactor).
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Direct measurements of biomethanation potential are also made using gas evolution or more recent gravimetric assays.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Anaerobic digestion is particularly suited to organic material, and is commonly used for industrial effluent, wastewater and sewage sludge treatment.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Anaerobic digestion, a simple process, can greatly reduce the amount of organic matter which might otherwise be destined to be dumped at sea, dumped in landfills, or burnt in incinerators.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Pressure from environmentally related legislation on solid waste disposal methods in developed countries has increased the application of anaerobic digestion as a process for reducing waste volumes and generating useful byproducts.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] It may either be used to process the source-separated fraction of municipal waste or alternatively combined with mechanical sorting systems, to process residual mixed municipal waste.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] These facilities are called mechanical biological treatment plants.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] If the putrescible waste processed in anaerobic digesters were disposed of in a landfill, it would break down naturally and often anaerobically.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] In this case, the gas will eventually escape into the atmosphere.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] As methane is about 20 times more potent as a greenhouse gas than carbon dioxide, this has significant negative environmental effects.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] In countries that collect household waste, the use of local anaerobic digestion facilities can help to reduce the amount of waste that requires transportation to centralized landfill sites or incineration facilities.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] This reduced burden on transportation reduces carbon emissions from the collection vehicles.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] If localized anaerobic digestion facilities are embedded within an electrical distribution network, they can help reduce the electrical losses associated with transporting electricity over a national grid.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Anaerobic digestion can be used for the remediation of sludge polluted with PFAS.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] A 2024 study has shown that anaerobic digestion, combined with adsorption in activated carbon and voltage application can remove up to 61% of PFAS from sewage sludge.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] In developing countries, simple home and farm-based anaerobic digestion systems offer the potential for low-cost energy for cooking and lighting.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] From 1975, China and India have both had large, government-backed schemes for adaptation of small biogas plants for use in the household for cooking and lighting.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] At present, projects for anaerobic digestion in the developing world can gain financial support through the United Nations Clean Development Mechanism if they are able to show they provide reduced carbon emissions.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Methane and power produced in anaerobic digestion facilities can be used to replace energy derived from fossil fuels, and hence reduce emissions of greenhouse gases, because the carbon in biodegradable material is part of a carbon cycle.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] The carbon released into the atmosphere from the combustion of biogas has been removed by plants for them to grow in the recent past, usually within the last decade, but more typically within the last growing season.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] If the plants are regrown, taking the carbon out of the atmosphere once more, the system will be carbon neutral.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] In contrast, carbon in fossil fuels has been sequestered in the earth for many millions of years, the combustion of which increases the overall levels of carbon dioxide in the atmosphere.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Power generation through anaerobic digesters is best suited to large-scale operations, rather than small farms, as large operations have the volume of manure that is able to make the systems financially viable.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Biogas from sewage sludge treatment is sometimes used to run a gas engine to produce electrical power, some or all of which can be used to run the sewage works.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Some waste heat from the engine is then used to heat the digester.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] The waste heat is, in general, enough to heat the digester to the required temperatures.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] The power potential from sewage works is limited – in the UK, there are about 80 MW total of such generation, with the potential to increase to 150 MW, which is insignificant compared to the average power demand in the UK of about 35,000 MW.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] The scope for biogas generation from nonsewage waste biological matter – energy crops, food waste, abattoir waste, etc. - is much higher, estimated to be capable of about 3,000 MW.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Farm biogas plants using animal waste and energy crops are expected to contribute to reducing CO2 emissions and strengthen the grid, while providing UK farmers with additional revenues.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Some countries offer incentives in the form of, for example, feed-in tariffs for feeding electricity onto the power grid to subsidize green energy production.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] In Oakland, California at the East Bay Municipal Utility District's main wastewater treatment plant (EBMUD), food waste is currently codigested with primary and secondary municipal wastewater solids and other high-strength wastes.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Compared to municipal wastewater solids digestion alone, food waste codigestion has many benefits.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Anaerobic digestion of food waste pulp from the EBMUD food waste process provides a higher normalized energy benefit, compared to municipal wastewater solids: 730 to 1,300 kWh per dry ton of food waste applied compared to 560 to 940 kWh per dry ton of municipal wastewater solids applied.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] The methane component of biogas can be concentrated through upgrading into biomethane.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Biomethane (also known as renewable natural gas) can be injected into the natural gas grid.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] The upgrading process removes contaminants such as hydrogen sulphide and siloxanes, as well as non-methane gas constituents, chiefly carbon dioxide.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Several technologies are available for this purpose, the most widely implemented being pressure swing adsorption (PSA), water or amine scrubbing (absorption processes) and membrane separation.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] After upgrading with the above-mentioned technologies, biomethane can be compressed into compressed natural gas and used in natural gas vehicles.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Use of natural gas vehicles is very extensive in Sweden, where over 38,600 gas vehicles exist, and 60% of the CNG supply is biomethane generated in anaerobic digestion plants.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] The solid, fibrous component of the digested material can be used as a soil conditioner to increase the organic content of soils.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Digester liquor can be used as a fertiliser to supply vital nutrients to soils instead of chemical fertilisers that require large amounts of energy to produce and transport.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] The use of manufactured fertilisers is, therefore, more carbon-intensive than the use of anaerobic digester liquor fertiliser.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] In countries such as Spain, where many soils are organically depleted, the markets for the digested solids can be equally as important as the biogas.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Anaerobic digestion can be used at a small scale to produce gas for cooking.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] The organic waste like fallen leaves, kitchen waste, food waste etc. are fed into a crusher unit, where it is mixed with a small amount of water.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] The mixture is then fed into the anaerobic digester, where the archaea decomposes it to produce cooking gas.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] A 2 cubic meter anaerobic digester can produce 2 cubic meters of cooking gas.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] The three principal products of anaerobic digestion are biogas, digestate, and water.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Biogas is the ultimate waste product of the microbes feeding off the input biodegradable feedstock and is mostly methane and carbon dioxide, with a small amount of hydrogen (H 2), water vapor (H 2O, amount depending on temperature), and trace hydrogen sulfide (H 2S).
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Most of the biogas is produced during the middle of the digestion, after the bacterial population has grown, and tapers off as the putrescible material is exhausted.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] The gas is normally stored on top of the digester in an inflatable gas bubble or extracted and stored next to the facility in a gas holder.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] The methane in biogas can be burned to produce both heat and electricity, usually with a reciprocating engine or microturbine often in a cogeneration arrangement where the electricity and waste heat generated are used to warm the digesters or to heat buildings.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Excess electricity can be sold to suppliers or put into the local grid.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Electricity produced by anaerobic digesters is considered to be renewable energy and may attract subsidies.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Biogas does not contribute to increasing atmospheric carbon dioxide concentrations because the gas is not released directly into the atmosphere and the carbon dioxide comes from an organic source with a short carbon cycle.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Biogas may require treatment or 'scrubbing' to refine it for use as a fuel.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Hydrogen sulfide, a toxic product formed from sulfates in the feedstock, is released as a trace component of the biogas.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] National environmental enforcement agencies, such as the U.S.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Alternatively, the addition of ferrous chloride FeCl2 to the digestion tanks inhibits hydrogen sulfide production.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Volatile siloxanes can also contaminate the biogas; such compounds are frequently found in household waste and wastewater.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] In digestion facilities accepting these materials as a component of the feedstock, low-molecular-weight siloxanes volatilise into biogas.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] When this gas is combusted in a gas engine, turbine, or boiler, siloxanes are converted into silicon dioxide (SiO2), which deposits internally in the machine, increasing wear and tear.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Practical and cost-effective technologies to remove siloxanes and other biogas contaminants are available at the present time.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] In certain applications, *in situ* treatment can be used to increase the methane purity by reducing the offgas carbon dioxide content, purging the majority of it in a secondary reactor.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] In countries such as Switzerland, Germany, and Sweden, the methane in the biogas may be compressed for it to be used as a vehicle transportation fuel or input directly into the gas mains.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] In countries where the driver for the use of anaerobic digestion are renewable electricity subsidies, this route of treatment is less likely, as energy is required in this processing stage and reduces the overall levels available to sell.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Digestate is the non-gaseous product of the digesters.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] It consists of remnants of the original input material to the digesters that the microbes cannot use and the mineralised remains of the dead bacteria from within the digesters.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] The acidogenic and methanogenic steps each produce a digestate product, which are fibrous and liquid respectively.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] In two-stage systems, different forms of digestate come from different digestion tanks.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] In single-stage digestion systems, the two fractions appear combined into a sludge and, if desired, can be separated by further processing.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] The acidogenic digestate is a stable, organic, fiborous material consisting largely of lignin and cellulose, but also of a variety of mineral components in a matrix of dead bacterial cells; some plastic may be present.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] The material resembles domestic compost and can be used as such.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] It can also be used as a lignocellulosic biomass to make low-grade building products such as fibreboard. or as feedstock for ethanol production.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] The methanogenic digestate is a liquid rich in plant nutrients (nitrogen as ammoniums and potassium), which can be used as a fertiliser, depending on the quality of the material being digested.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Levels of potentially toxic elements (PTEs) should be chemically assessed.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] This will depend upon the quality of the original feedstock.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] In the case of most clean and source-separated biodegradable waste streams, the levels of PTEs will be low.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] In the case of wastes originating from industry, the levels of PTEs may be higher and will need to be taken into consideration when determining a suitable end use for the material.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Acidogenic digestate typically contains biopolymers, such as lignin, that cannot be broken down by the anaerobic microorganisms.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Methanogenic digestate may contain ammonia at phytotoxic levels and may hamper the growth of plants if it is used as a soil-improving material.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] For these two reasons, a maturation or composting stage may be employed after digestion.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Lignin and other materials are available for degradation by aerobic microorganisms such as fungi.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] During maturation, ammonia is oxidized into nitrates which improves the fertility of the material as a soil amendment.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] In addition, composting leads to significant mass loss (primarily through evaporation) reducing the amount of material that needs to be trucked off-site.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] Composting is often used in dry digesters, as wet digesters require bulking with wood products or other material to be compostable.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] As most digesters are unable to degrade compostable packaging, secondary composting is required for this sort of packaging to be processed in an anaerobic digester.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] The final output from anaerobic digestion systems is water, which originates both from the moisture content of the original waste that was treated and water produced during the microbial reactions in the digestion systems.
[src:alcohol-fuel/anaerobic-digestion] This water may be released from the dewatering of the digestate or may be implicitly separate from the digestate.
